# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bernicia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bernicia/adda-of-bernicia] Adda was one of several sons born to Ida, the first ruler of Bernicia, as was his successor Æthelric.
[src:bernicia/adda-of-bernicia] Adda may have been the Bernician commander at the battle of Caer Greu, where the British kings Peredur and Gwrgi of Ebrauc were killed.
[src:bernicia/adda-of-bernicia] There is some confusion here because of a conflict between sources.
[src:bernicia/adda-of-bernicia] The Annales Cambriae state that the Battle of Caer Greu took place in 580.
[src:bernicia/adda-of-bernicia] The evidence for Adda being the Bernician king in question is that the Welsh Triads identify that leader as Ida.
[src:bernicia/adda-of-bernicia] Since the sources agree that Ida died in 559, it is assumed that the Triads have named Ida by mistake, and that Adda—the only son with a name similar to Ida's -- was meant.
[src:bernicia/adda-of-bernicia] However, the Historia Brittonum states that Adda only reigned for 8 years after Ida, in which case either the Bernician leader must have been one of Adda's successors, or else one of the sources has the dates confused.
[src:bernicia/adda-of-bernicia] It is also possible that Ælle of Deira led the Angles at Caer Greu—certainly, Ebrauc ceased to exist as a British kingdom after the battle, with Deira taking over its territory.
[src:bernicia/adda-of-bernicia] Since, however, the surviving northern British kingdoms subsequently combined to launch a vigorous campaign directed against Bernicia rather than Deira, this suggests that Bernicia was the original combatant.
[src:bernicia/adda-of-bernicia] Nothing else is known for certain about Adda's life or reign.
[src:bernicia/adda-of-bernicia] The earliest authorities differ widely on the order and the regnal years of the Bernician kings between the death of Ida and the beginning of Æthelfrith's rule in 592/593.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the period 1150 to 1300, warm dry summers and less severe winters allowed cultivation at much greater heights and made land more productive.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Arable farming grew significantly, but was still more common in low-lying areas than in high-lying areas such as the Highlands, Galloway and the Southern Uplands.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The system of infield and outfield agriculture, a variation of open-field farming widely used across Europe, may have been introduced with feudalism from the twelfth century.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Crops were bere (a form of barley), oats and sometimes wheat, rye and legumes.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Hunting reserves were adopted by Anglo-Norman lords and then by Gaelic ones.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The more extensive outfield was used for oats.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] New monastic orders such as the Cistercians became major landholders and sheep farmers, particularly in the Borders where they were organised in granges.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] By the late Medieval period, most farming was based on the Lowland fermtoun or Highland baile, settlements of a handful of families that jointly farmed an area notionally suitable for two or three plough teams, allocated in run rigs to tenant farmers, known as husbandmen.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Runrigs usually ran downhill so that they included both wet and dry land.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Most ploughing was done with a heavy wooden plough with an iron coulter, pulled by oxen, which were more effective and cheaper to feed than horses.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Sheep and goats were probably the main sources of milk, while cattle were raised for meat.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The rural economy appears to have boomed in the thirteenth century and in the immediate aftermath of the Black Death was still buoyant, but by the 1360s there was a severe falling off in incomes to be followed by a slow recovery in the fifteenth century.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Scotland is roughly half the size of England and Wales and has approximately the same amount of coastline, but only between a fifth and a sixth of the amount of the arable or good pastoral land, under 60 metres above sea level, and most of this is located in the south and east.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This made marginal pastoral farming and fishing, the key factors in the pre-modern economy.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Its east Atlantic position means that it has moderate rainfall: today about 700 mm per year in the east and over 1,000 mm in the west.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This encouraged the spread of blanket peat bog, the acidity of which, combined with high level of wind and salt spray, made most of the western islands treeless.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The existence of hills, mountains, quicksands and marshes made agriculture and internal communication difficult.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The early Middle Ages, from the fifth century to the tenth century, were a period of climate deterioration, with a drop in temperature and an increase in rainfall, resulting in more land becoming unproductive.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] With a lack of significant transport links and wider markets, most farms had to produce a self-sufficient diet of meat, dairy products and cereals, supplemented by hunter-gathering.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The climate meant that more oats and barley were grown than wheat.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The evidence of bones indicates that cattle were by far the most important domesticated animal, followed by pigs, sheep and goats, while domesticated fowl were very rare.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Christian missionaries from Ireland may have changed agricultural practice, bringing innovations such as the horizontal watermill and mould board ploughs, which were more effective in turning the soil.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the period 1150 to 1300, warm dry summers and less severe winters of the Medieval Warm Period allowed cultivation at much greater heights above sea level and made land more productive.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Arable farming grew significantly, but was still more common in low-lying areas in the south and east than in high-lying areas such as the Highlands, Galloway and the Southern Uplands.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The feudalism introduced under David I, particularly in the east and south where the crown's authority was greatest, saw the placement of baronial lordships.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Land was now held from the king, or a superior lord, in exchange for loyalty and forms of service that were usually military.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Barons, who held feudal tenures, had the right to hold baronial courts, which could deal with matters of land ownership.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, the imposition of feudalism continued to sit beside the existing systems of landholding and tenure and it is not clear how this change impacted on the lives of the ordinary free and unfree workers.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In places, feudalism may have tied workers more closely to the land.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, the predominantly pastoral nature of Scottish agriculture may have made the imposition of a manorial system, based on the English model, impracticable in some areas.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Obligations appear to have been limited to occasional labour service, seasonal renders of food, hospitality and money rents.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They usually included supplying oxen for ploughing the lord's land on an annual basis and the much resented obligation to grind corn at the lord's mill.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Hunting reserves were adopted by Anglo-Norman lords and then by Gaelic ones, creating large tracts of land reserved for the leisure of the aristocracy and nobility.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were less rigorously enforced than in England, where the taking of wood and game were strictly forbidden, and all royal forests were on land already in the king's hands.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The introduction of new monastic orders such as the Cistercians in this period also brought innovations in agriculture.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Particularly in the Borders, their monasteries became major landholders, sheep farmers and producers of wool for the markets in Flanders.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were organised in granges, monastic farms run by lay brothers of the order.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Granges were theoretically within 30 miles of the mother monastery, so that those working there could return for services on Sundays and feast days.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were used for variety of purposes, including pastoral, arable and industrial production.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, to manage more distant assets in Ayrshire, Melrose Abbey used Mauchline as a "super grange", to oversee lesser granges.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Some abbeys like Melrose had at least 12,000 sheep in the late thirteenth century.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The system of infield and outfield agriculture, a variation of open field farming widely used across Europe, may have been introduced with feudalism and would continue until the eighteenth century.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This expanded from the use of small enclosed fields, which continued from the prehistoric era.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The infield was the best land, close to housing.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It was farmed continuously and most intensively, receiving most of the manure.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Crops were usually bere (a form of barley), oats and sometimes wheat, rye and legumes.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The more extensive outfield was used for largely for oats.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It was fertilised from the overnight folding of cattle in the summer and was often left fallow to recover its fertility.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In fertile regions the infield could be extensive, but in the uplands it might be small, surrounded by large amounts of outfield.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In coastal areas fertiliser included seaweed and around the major burghs urban refuse was used.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Yields were fairly low, often around three times the quantity of seed sown, although they could reach twice that yield on some infields.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The main unit of land measurement in Scotland was the *davoch* (i.e.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This unit is also known as the "Scottish ploughgate".
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In English-speaking Lothian, it was simply a ploughgate.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It may have measured about 104 acres (0.42 km2), divided into 4 *raths* or eight *oxgangs*, the area that eight oxen were said to be able to plough in one year.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] By the fourteenth century most farming was based on the Lowland fermtoun or Highland baile, settlements of a handful of families that jointly farmed an area notionally suitable for two or three plough teams.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were allocated in run rigs to tenant farmers, who were usually known as husbandmen or bonders.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The average amount of land used by a husbandman in Scotland, known as a husbandland, was 26 acres, or 2 oxgangs.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They would also have had a share of hay meadow and common pasture.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Below the husbandmen, lesser landholders and free tenants, were the cottars, who often shared rights to common pasture, occupied small portions of land and participated in joint farming as hired labour.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Farms also might have grassmen, who had rights only to grazing.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Pasture was often accessed by shieling-grounds, with shelters made of stone or turf, used for the grazing of cattle in summer.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These would often be distant from the main settlements in the Lowlands, but might be relatively close in the more remote Highlands.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Runrigs, were a ridge and furrow pattern, similar to that used in parts of England, with alternating "runs" (furrows) and "rigs" (ridges).
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They usually ran downhill so that they included both wet and dry land, helping to offset some of the problems of extreme weather conditions.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Most ploughing was done with a heavy wooden plough with an iron coulter, pulled by oxen, which were more effective on heavy soils and cheaper to feed than horses.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were usually pulled by a team of eight oxen, which would have taken four men to operate and only covered half an acre a day.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Key crops included kale (for both humans and animals), and hemp and flax for cloth production.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Sheep and goats were probably the main sources of milk, while cattle were raised primarily for meat.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This was followed by a slow recovery in the fifteenth century.
[src:bernicia/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Towards the end of the period average temperatures began to reduce again, with the cooler and wetter conditions of the Little Ice Age limiting the extent of arable agriculture, particularly in the Highlands.
[src:bernicia/alvingham] The village is mentioned in the Domesday Book of 1086 as "Aluingeham", meaning "Homestead of the Ælfingas (the tribe of Ælf)".
[src:bernicia/alvingham] It was the location of a Gilbertine Alvingham Priory until the dissolution of the monasteries.
[src:bernicia/alvingham] In the pre-Norman period, as the Lincolnshire coastline grew further into what had previously been tidal salt marsh, people from Alvingham settled the nearby village of Conisholme.
[src:bernicia/alvingham] The 16th-century poet and translator Barnabe Googe inherited lands of the former Alvingham Priory after his father's death.
[src:bernicia/alvingham] Alvingham Mill is mentioned in the Domesday Book.
[src:bernicia/alvingham] In the west of the parish, the village borders Keddington.
[src:bernicia/alvingham] The parish boundary meets Brackenborough with Little Grimsby, east of Brackenborough Wood.
[src:bernicia/alvingham] Passing northwards, it meets Yarburgh, and crosses the Alvingham–Yarburgh road near Newholme.
[src:bernicia/alvingham] It follows Black Dike in a north-east direction, north of America Farm.
[src:bernicia/alvingham] Where it crosses the north–south Louth Canal, it briefly meets Grainthorpe.
[src:bernicia/alvingham] On Alvingham Fen it meets Conisholme and the Seven Towns North Eau, one of the constituents of the River Lud as it approaches the coast.
[src:bernicia/alvingham] Directly to the east is a large wind farm on Conisholme Fen.
[src:bernicia/alvingham] The boundary follows the Seven Towns North Eau southwards, to the west of Nunnitts Farm (outside the parish).
[src:bernicia/alvingham] It meets North Cockerington at the point the Seven Towns North Eau, Seven Towns South Eau, and Old Eau meet to form the River Lud.
[src:bernicia/alvingham] The river (and parish boundary) runs parallel, to the south, to the Louth Canal.
[src:bernicia/alvingham] The village is noted for containing two churches in the same churchyard.
[src:bernicia/alvingham] One, the now redundant St Mary's was previously the church of the neighbouring parish of North Cockerington, and is now under the care of the Churches Conservation Trust.
[src:bernicia/alvingham] The other, Alvingham's parish church of St Adelwold's, was restored in 1933 after being unused for most of the 19th century.
[src:bernicia/alvingham] Adelwold's was built on the foundations of an earlier Saxon church and is the only British church dedicated to the Saxon Saint Adelwold.
[src:bernicia/alvingham] St Adelwold (Alvingham with Yarburgh and North Cockerington) is in the Mid Marsh group of churches with Great Carlton, South Cockerington, and Grimoldby, and based in Grimoldby.
[src:bernicia/alvingham] The religious parish is larger than the civil parish, as it includes North Cockerington, a civil parish.
[src:bernicia/alvingham] The village has a Women's Institute and a farm shop.
[src:bernicia/alvingham] Alvingham Village Hall holds events for the village and the wider local area, including an 'Open Mic' night for musical talent.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] The **Angevins** (/ˈændʒɪvɪnz/; "of/from Anjou") were a royal house of French origin that ruled England, Ireland and parts of France in the 12th and early 13th centuries; its monarchs were Henry II, Richard I and John.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry II won control of a vast assemblage of lands in western Europe that would last for 80 years and would retrospectively be referred to as the Angevin Empire.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] As a political entity this was structurally different from the preceding Norman and subsequent Plantagenet realms.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Geoffrey of Anjou became Duke of Normandy in 1144 and died in 1151.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] In 1152, his heir, Henry, added Aquitaine by virtue of his marriage to Eleanor of Aquitaine.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] In 1189, Henry was succeeded by his third son, Richard, whose reputation for martial prowess won him the epithet "*Cœur de Lion*" or "Lionheart".
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] He was born and raised in England but spent very little time there during his adult life, perhaps as little as six months.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Despite this Richard remains an enduring iconic figure both in England and in France, and is one of very few kings of England remembered by his nickname as opposed to regnal number.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] When Richard died, his brother John – Henry's fifth and last surviving son – took the throne.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] In 1204, John lost many of the Angevins' continental territories, including Anjou, to the French crown.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] He and his successors were still recognized as dukes of Aquitaine.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] The loss of Anjou, for which the dynasty is named, and other French fiefs made John the last of the Angevin kings of England.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] However, there is no agreement among historians.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Some make no distinction between Angevins and Plantagenets while considering Henry II as the first Plantagenet king.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] From John, the dynasty continued on the throne of England and unbroken in the senior male line until the reign of Richard II before dividing into two competing cadet branches, the House of Lancaster and the House of York.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] In the 17th century, historians would use the term "Plantagenet" when describing the house.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] In addition, it is also used pertaining to Anjou, or any sovereign, government derived from this.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] As a noun, it is used for any native of Anjou or Angevin ruler.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Richard of York, 3rd Duke of York, adopted Plantagenet as his family name in the 15th century.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] *Plantegenest* (or *Plante Genest*) had been a 12th-century nickname for his ancestor Geoffrey, Count of Anjou and Duke of Normandy.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] One of many popular theories suggests the blossom of common broom, a bright yellow ("gold") flowering plant, genista in medieval Latin, as the source of the nickname.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] It is uncertain why Richard chose this specific name, although, during the Wars of the Roses, it emphasised Richard's status as Geoffrey's patrilineal descendant.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] The retrospective usage of the name for all of Geoffrey's male-line descendants was popular during the subsequent Tudor dynasty, perhaps encouraged by the further legitimacy it gave to Richard's great-grandson, Henry VIII.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] In the late 17th century, this name passed into common usage among historians.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] The Angevins descend from Geoffrey II, Count of Gâtinais and Ermengarde of Anjou.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] In 1060 this couple inherited, via cognatic kinship, the county of Anjou from an older line dating from 870 and a noble called Ingelger.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] The marriage of their great-grandson, Geoffrey V, Count of Anjou to Matilda, the only surviving legitimate child of Henry I of England, was part of a struggle for power during the tenth and eleventh centuries among the lords of Normandy, Brittany, Poitou, Blois, Maine and the kings of France.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] It was from this marriage that Geoffrey's son, Henry, inherited the claims to England, Normandy and Anjou that marks the beginning of the Angevin and Plantagenet dynasties.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] This was the third attempt by Geoffrey's father Fulk V to build a political alliance with Normandy.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] The first was by marrying his daughter Matilda to Henry's heir William Adelin, who drowned in the wreck of the *White Ship*.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Fulk then married his daughter Sibylla to William Clito, heir to Henry's older brother Robert Curthose, but Henry had the marriage annulled to avoid strengthening William's rival claim to his lands.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] As society became more prosperous and stable in the 11th century, inheritance customs developed that allowed daughters (in the absence of sons) to succeed to principalities as well as landed estates.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] The twelfth-century chronicler Ralph de Diceto noted that the counts of Anjou extended their dominion over their neighbours by marriage rather than conquest.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] The marriage of Geoffrey to the daughter of a king (and widow of an emperor) occurred in this context.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] It is unknown whether King Henry intended to make Geoffrey his heir, but it is known that the threat presented by William Clito's rival claim to the duchy of Normandy made his negotiating position very weak.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Even so, it is probable that, should the marriage be childless, King Henry would have attempted to be succeeded by one of his Norman kinsmen such as Theobald II, Count of Champagne, or Stephen of Blois, who in the event did seize King Henry's English crown.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] King Henry's great relief in 1133 at the birth of a son to the couple, described as "the heir to the Kingdom", is understandable in the light of this situation.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Following this, the birth of a second son raised the question of whether custom would be followed with the maternal inheritance passing to first born and the paternal inheritance going to his brother, Geoffrey.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] According to William of Newburgh, writing in the 1190s, the plan failed because of Geoffrey's early death in 1151.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry's brother Geoffrey died in 1158, too soon to receive Anjou, but not before being installed count in Nantes after Henry aided a rebellion by its citizens against their previous lord.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] The unity of Henry's assemblage of domains was largely dependent on the ruling family, influencing the opinion of most historians that this instability made it unlikely to endure.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] The French custom of partible inheritance at the time would lead to political fragmentation.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Indeed, if Henry II's sons Henry the Young King and Geoffrey of Brittany had not died young, the inheritance of 1189 would have been fundamentally altered.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry and Richard both planned for partition on their deaths while attempting to provide overriding sovereignty to hold the lands together.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] For example, in 1173 and 1183, Henry tried to force Richard to acknowledge allegiance to his older brother for the duchy of Aquitaine, and later Richard would confiscate Ireland from John.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] This was complicated by the Angevins being subjects of the kings of France, who felt these feudal rights of homage and the right of allegiance more legally belonged to them.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] This was particularly true when the wardship of Geoffrey's son Arthur and lordship of Brittany was contended between 1202 and 1204.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Upon the Young King's death in 1183, Richard became heir in chief, but refused to give up Aquitaine to give John an inheritance.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] More by accident than design this meant that, while Richard inherited the patrimony, John would become lord of Ireland and Arthur would be duke of Brittany.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] By the mid-thirteenth century, there was a clear unified patrimony and Plantagenet empire but this cannot be called an *Angevin Empire* as by this date Anjou and most of the continental lands had been lost.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry I of England named his daughter Matilda heir; but when he died in 1135 Matilda was far from England in Anjou or Maine, while her cousin Stephen was closer in Boulogne, giving him the advantage he needed to race to England and have himself crowned and anointed king of England.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Matilda's husband Geoffrey, though he had little interest in England, commenced a long struggle for the duchy of Normandy.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] To create a second front, Matilda landed in England during 1139 to challenge Stephen, instigating the civil war known as the Anarchy.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] In 1141, she captured Stephen at the battle of Lincoln, prompting the collapse of his support.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] While Geoffrey pushed on with the conquest of Normandy over the next four years, Matilda threw away her position through arrogance and inability to be magnanimous in victory.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] She was even forced to release Stephen in a hostage exchange for her half-brother Robert, 1st Earl of Gloucester, allowing Stephen to resume control of much of England.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Geoffrey never visited England to offer practical assistance, but instead sent Henry as a male figurehead—beginning in 1142 when Henry was only 9—with a view that if England was conquered it would be Henry that would become king.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] In 1150, Geoffrey also transferred the title of Duke of Normandy to Henry but retained the dominant role in governance.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry faced many challenges to secure possession of his father's and grandfathers' lands that required the reassertion and extension of old suzerainties.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] In 1162 Theobald, Archbishop of Canterbury, died, and Henry saw an opportunity to re-establish what he saw as his rights over the church in England by appointing his friend Thomas Becket to succeed him.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Instead, Becket proved to be an inept politician whose defiance alienated the king and his counsellors.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry and Becket clashed repeatedly: over church tenures, Henry's brother's marriage and taxation.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry reacted by getting Becket, and other members of the English episcopate, to recognise sixteen ancient customs—governing relations between the king, his courts, and the church—in writing for the first time in the Constitutions of Clarendon.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] When Becket tried to leave the country without permission, Henry attempted to ruin him by laying a number of suits relating to Becket's time as chancellor.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] In response Becket fled into exile for five years.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Relations later improved, allowing Becket's return, but soured again when Becket saw the coronation of Henry's son as coregent by the Archbishop of York as a challenge to his authority and excommunicated those who had offended him.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Within Christian Europe Henry was widely considered complicit in Becket's death.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] The opinion of this transgression against the church made Henry a pariah, so in penance he walked barefoot into Canterbury Cathedral where he was scourged by monks.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] In 1171, Henry invaded Ireland to assert his overlordship following alarm at the success of knights that he had allowed to recruit soldiers in England and Wales, who had assumed the role of colonisers and accrued autonomous power, including Strongbow.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Pope Adrian IV had given Henry a papal blessing to expand his power into Ireland to reform the Irish church.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Originally, this would have allowed some territory to be granted to Henry's brother, William, but other matters had distracted Henry and William was now dead.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Instead, Henry's designs were made plain when he gave the lordship of Ireland to his youngest son, John.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] In 1172, Henry II tried to give his landless youngest son John a wedding gift of the three castles of Chinon, Loudun and Mirebeau.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] This angered the 18-year-old Young King, who had yet to receive any lands from his father, and prompted a rebellion by Henry II's wife and three eldest sons.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Louis VII supported the rebellion to destabilise Henry II.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] William the Lion and other subjects of Henry II also joined the revolt and it took 18 months for Henry to force the rebels to submit to his authority.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] In Le Mans in 1182, Henry II gathered his children to plan a partible inheritance in which his eldest son (also called Henry) would inherit England, Normandy and Anjou; Richard the Duchy of Aquitaine; Geoffrey Brittany, and John Ireland.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] The younger Henry rebelled again before he died of dysentery and, in 1186, Geoffrey died after a tournament accident.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] In 1189, Richard and Philip II of France took advantage of Henry's failing health and forced him to accept humiliating peace terms, including naming Richard as his sole heir.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Two days later, the old king died, defeated and miserable in the knowledge that even his favoured son John had rebelled.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] This fate was seen as the price he paid for the murder of Beckett.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] On the day of Richard's English coronation, there was a mass slaughter of Jews, described by Richard of Devizes as a "holocaust".
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] After his coronation, Richard put the Angevin Empire's affairs in order before joining the Third Crusade to the Middle East in early 1190.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Opinions of Richard by his contemporaries varied.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] He had rejected and humiliated the king of France's sister; deposed the king of Cyprus and sold the island; insulted and refused to give spoils from the Third Crusade to Leopold V, Duke of Austria, and allegedly arranged the assassination of Conrad of Montferrat.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] His cruelty was exemplified by the massacre of 2,600 prisoners in Acre.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] However, Richard was respected for his military leadership and courtly manners.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Despite victories in the Third Crusade he failed to capture Jerusalem, retreating from the Holy Land with a small band of followers.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Richard was captured by Leopold on his return journey.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] He was transferred to Henry VI, Holy Roman Emperor, and a 25-percent tax on goods and income was required to pay his 150,000-mark ransom.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Philip II of France had overrun Normandy, while John of England controlled much of Richard's remaining lands.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] However, when Richard returned to England he forgave John and re-established his control.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Leaving England permanently in 1194, Richard fought Philip for five years for the return of holdings seized during his incarceration.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] On the brink of victory, he was wounded by an arrow during the siege of Château de Châlus-Chabrol and died ten days later.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] His failure to produce an heir caused a succession crisis.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Anjou, Brittany, Maine and Touraine chose Richard's nephew Arthur as heir, while John succeeded in England and Normandy.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Philip II of France again destabilised the Plantagenet territories on the European mainland, supporting his vassal Arthur's claim to the English crown.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Eleanor supported her son John, who was victorious at the Battle of Mirebeau and captured the rebel leadership.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Arthur was murdered (allegedly by John), and his sister Eleanor would spend the rest of her life in captivity.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] John's behaviour drove a number of French barons to side with Philip, and the resulting rebellions by Norman and Angevin barons ended John's control of his continental possessions—the *de facto* end of the Angevin Empire, although Henry III would maintain his claim until 1259.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] After re-establishing his authority in England, John planned to retake Normandy and Anjou by drawing the French from Paris while another army (under Otto IV, Holy Roman Emperor) attacked from the north.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] However, his allies were defeated at the Battle of Bouvines in one of the most decisive battles in French history.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] John's nephew Otto retreated and was soon overthrown, with John agreeing to a five-year truce.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Philip's victory was crucial to the political order in England and France, and the battle was instrumental in establishing absolute monarchy in France.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] John's French defeats weakened his position in England.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] The rebellion of his English vassals resulted in *Magna Carta*, which limited royal power and established common law.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] This would form the basis of every constitutional battle of the 13th and 14th centuries.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] The barons and the crown failed to abide by *Magna Carta*, leading to the First Barons' War when rebel barons provoked an invasion by Prince Louis.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Many historians use John's death and William Marshall's appointment as protector of nine-year-old Henry III to mark the end of the Angevin period and the beginning of the Plantagenet dynasty.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Marshall won the war with victories at Lincoln and Dover in 1217, leading to the Treaty of Lambeth in which Louis renounced his claims.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] In victory, the Marshal Protectorate reissued *Magna Carta* as the basis of future government.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Historians use the period of Prince Louis's invasion to mark the end of the Angevin period and the beginning of the Plantagenet dynasty.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] The outcome of the military situation was uncertain at John's death; William Marshall saved the dynasty, forcing Louis to renounce his claim with a military victory.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] However, Philip had captured all the Angevin possessions in France except Gascony.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] This collapse had several causes, including long-term changes in economic power, growing cultural differences between England and Normandy and (in particular) the fragile, familial nature of Henry's empire.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry III continued his attempts to reclaim Normandy and Anjou until 1259, but John's continental losses and the consequent growth of Capetian power during the 13th century marked a "turning point in European history".
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Richard of York adopted "Plantagenet" as a family name for himself and his descendants during the 15th century.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] *Plantegenest* (or *Plante Genest*) was Geoffrey's nickname, and his emblem may have been the common broom (*planta genista* in medieval Latin).
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] It is uncertain why Richard chose the name, but it emphasised Richard's hierarchal status as Geoffrey's (and six English kings') patrilineal descendant during the Wars of the Roses.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] The retrospective use of the name for Geoffrey's male descendants was popular during the Tudor period, perhaps encouraged by the added legitimacy it gave Richard's great-grandson Henry VIII of England.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Through John, descent from the Angevins (legitimate and illegitimate) is widespread, and includes all subsequent monarchs of England and the United Kingdom.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] John also had illegitimate children with a number of mistresses, including nine sons—Richard, Oliver, John, Geoffrey, Henry, Osbert Gifford, Eudes, Bartholomew and (probably) Philip—and three daughters—Joan, Maud and (probably) Isabel.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Of these, Joan was the best known, since she married Prince Llywelyn the Great of Wales.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] The chronicler Gerald of Wales borrowed elements of the Melusine legend to give the Angevins a demonic origin, and the kings were said to tell jokes about the stories.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry was widely criticised by contemporaries, even in his own court.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Nevertheless, William of Newburgh, writing after his death, commented that "the experience of present evils has revived the memory of his good deeds, and the man who in his own time was hated by all men, is now declared to have been an excellent and beneficent prince".
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry's son Richard's contemporary image was more nuanced, since he was the first king who was also a knight.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Known as a valiant, competent and generous military leader, he was criticised by chroniclers for taxing the clergy for the Crusade and his ransom; clergy were usually exempt from taxes.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Chroniclers Richard of Devizes, William of Newburgh, Roger of Hoveden and Ralph de Diceto were generally unsympathetic to John's behaviour under Richard, but more tolerant of the earliest years of John's reign.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Accounts of the middle and later years of his reign are limited to Gervase of Canterbury and Ralph of Coggeshall, neither of whom were satisfied with John's performance as king.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] His later negative reputation was established by two chroniclers writing after the king's death: Roger of Wendover and Matthew Paris.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] The latter claimed that John attempted to convert to Islam, but this is not believed by modern historians.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Many of the changes Henry introduced during his rule had long-term consequences.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] His legal innovations form part of the basis for English law, with the Exchequer of Pleas a forerunner of the Common Bench at Westminster.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry's itinerant justices also influenced his contemporaries' legal reforms: Philip Augustus's creation of itinerant *bailli*, for example, drew on Henry's model.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry's intervention in Brittany, Wales and Scotland had a significant long-term impact on the development of their societies and governments.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] John's reign, despite its flaws, and his signing of *Magna Carta*, were seen by Whig historians as positive steps in the constitutional development of England and part of a progressive and universalist course of political and economic development in medieval England.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Winston Churchill said, "[W]hen the long tally is added, it will be seen that the British nation and the English-speaking world owe far more to the vices of John than to the labours of virtuous sovereigns".
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] *Magna Carta* was reissued by the Marshal Protectorate and later as a foundation of future government.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] The Angevins were closely associated with the Fontevraud Abbey in Anjou.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] The abbey was originally the site of his grave and those of Eleanor, Richard, his daughter Joan, grandson Raymond VII of Toulouse and John's wife—Isabella of Angoulême.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry III visited the abbey in 1254 to reorder these tombs and requested that his heart be buried with them.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] According to historian John Gillingham, Henry and his reign have attracted historians for many years and Richard (whose reputation has "fluctuated wildly") is remembered largely because of his military exploits.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Interpretations of *Magna Carta* and the role of the rebel barons in 1215 have been revised; although the charter's symbolic, constitutional value for later generations is unquestionable, for most historians it is a failed peace agreement between factions.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] John's opposition to the papacy and his promotion of royal rights and prerogatives won favour from 16th-century Tudors.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] John Foxe, William Tyndale and Robert Barnes viewed John as an early Protestant hero, and Foxe included the king in his *Book of Martyrs*.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] John Speed's 1632 *Historie of Great Britaine* praised John's "great renown" as king, blaming biased medieval chroniclers for the king's poor reputation.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Similarly, later Protestant historians view Henry's role in Thomas Becket's death and his disputes with the French as worthy of praise.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Similarly, increased access to contemporary records during the late Victorian era led to a recognition of Henry's contributions to the evolution of English law and the exchequer.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] William Stubbs called Henry a "legislator king" because of his responsibility for major, long-term reforms in England; in contrast, Richard was "a bad son, a bad husband, a selfish ruler, and a vicious man".
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] The growth of the British Empire led historian Kate Norgate to begin detailed research into Henry's continental possessions and create the term "Angevin Empire" during the 1880s.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] However, 20th-century historians challenged many of these conclusions.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] During the 1950s, Jacques Boussard, John Jolliffe and others focused on the nature of Henry's "empire"; French scholars, in particular, analysed the mechanics of royal power during this period.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Anglocentric aspects of many histories of Henry's reign were challenged beginning in the 1980s, with efforts to unite British and French historical analyses of the period.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Detailed study of Henry's written records has cast doubt on earlier interpretations; Robert Eyton's 1878 volume (tracing Henry's itinerary by deductions from pipe rolls), for example, has been criticised for not acknowledging uncertainty.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Although many of Henry's royal charters have been identified, their interpretation, the financial information in the pipe rolls and broad economic data from his reign has proven more challenging than once thought.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Significant gaps in the historical analysis of Henry remain, particularly about his rule in Anjou and the south of France.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Interest in the morality of historical figures and scholars waxed during the Victorian period, leading to increased criticism of Henry's behaviour and Becket's death.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Historians relied on the judgement of chroniclers to focus on John's ethos.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Norgate wrote that John's downfall was due not to his military failures but his "almost superhuman wickedness", and James Ramsay blamed John's family background and innate cruelty for his downfall.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Richard's sexuality has been controversial since the 1940s, when John Harvey challenged what he saw as "the conspiracy of silence" surrounding the king's homosexuality with chronicles of Richard's behaviour, two public confessions, penances and childless marriage.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Opinion remains divided, with Gillingham arguing against Richard's homosexuality and Jean Flori acknowledging its possibility.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] According to recent biographers Ralph Turner and Lewis Warren, although John was an unsuccessful monarch, his failings were exaggerated by 12th- and 13th-century chroniclers.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Jim Bradbury echoes the contemporary consensus that John was a "hard-working administrator, an able man, an able general" with, as Turner suggests, "distasteful, even dangerous personality traits".
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] John Gillingham (author of a biography of Richard I) agrees and judges John to be a less-effective general than Turner and Warren do.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Bradbury takes a middle view, suggesting that modern historians have been overly lenient in evaluating John's flaws.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Popular historian Frank McLynn wrote that the king's modern reputation amongst historians is "bizarre" and, as a monarch, John "fails almost all those [tests] that can be legitimately set".
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry II appears as a fictionalised character in several modern plays and films.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] The king is a central character in James Goldman's play *The Lion in Winter* (1966), depicting an imaginary encounter between Henry's family and Philip Augustus over Christmas 1183 at Chinon.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Philip's strong character contrasts with John, an "effete weakling".
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] In the 1968 film, Henry is a sacrilegious, fiery and determined king.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry also appears in Jean Anouilh's play *Becket*, which was filmed in 1964.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Eliot's play *Murder in the Cathedral*, an exploration of Becket's death and Eliot's religious interpretation of it.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] During the Tudor period, popular representations of John emerged.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] He appeared as a "proto-Protestant martyr" in the anonymous play *The Troublesome Reign of King John* and John Bale's morality play *Kynge Johan*, in which John attempts to save England from the "evil agents of the Roman Church".Curren-Aquino 1989, p.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] 19 Shakespeare's anti-Catholic *King John* draws on *The Troublesome Reign*, offering a "balanced, dual view of a complex monarch as both a proto-Protestant victim of Rome's machinations and as a weak, selfishly motivated ruler".Curren-Aquino 1989, p.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] 19 Anthony Munday's plays *The Downfall and The Death of Robert Earl of Huntington* demonstrate many of John's negative traits, but approve of the king's stand against the Roman Catholic Church.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Richard is the subject of two operas: In 1719, George Frideric Handel used Richard's invasion of Cyprus as the plot for *Riccardo Primo*, and, in 1784, André Grétry wrote *Richard Coeur-de-lion*.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] The earliest ballads of Robin Hood such as those compiled in *A Gest of Robyn Hode* associated the character with a king named "Edward" and the setting is usually attributed by scholars to either the 13th or the 14th century.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Holt notes at some time around the 16th century, tales of Robin Hood started to mention him as a contemporary and supporter of Richard, Robin being driven to outlawry during John's misrule, while in the narratives Richard was largely absent, away at the Third Crusade.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Plays such as Robert Davenport's *King John and Matilda* further developed the Elizabethan works in the mid-17th century, focussing on John's tyranny and transferring the role of Protestant champion to the barons.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Graham Tulloch noted that unfavourable 19th-century fictionalised depictions of John were influenced by Sir Walter Scott's historical romance *Ivanhoe*.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] They, in turn, influenced the children's author Howard Pyle's *The Merry Adventures of Robin Hood* (1883) which cast John as the principal villain of the Robin Hood narrative.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] During the 20th century, John also appeared in fictional books and films with Robin Hood.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Sam De Grasse's John, in the 1922 film version, commits atrocities and acts of torture.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Claude Rains' John, in the 1938 version with Errol Flynn, began a cinematic trend in which John was an "effeminate ... arrogant and cowardly stay-at-home".
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] John's character highlights Richard's virtues and contrasts with Guy of Gisbourne, the "swashbuckling villain" opposing Robin.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] In the Disney cartoon version, John (voiced by Peter Ustinov) is a "cowardly, thumbsucking lion".
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] During the 13th century, a folktale developed in which Richard's minstrel Blondel roamed (singing a song known only to him and Richard) to find Richard's prison.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] This story was the foundation of André Ernest Modeste Grétry's opera *Richard Coeur-de-Lion*, and inspired the opening of Richard Thorpe's film version of *Ivanhoe*.
[src:bernicia/angevin-kings-of-england] Sixteenth-century tales of Robin Hood began describing him as a contemporary (and supporter) of Richard the Lionheart; Robin became an outlaw during the reign of Richard's evil brother, John, while Richard was fighting in the Third Crusade.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] The **Angles** (Old English: *Engle*, Latin: *Anglii*) were one of the main Germanic peoples who settled in Great Britain in the post-Roman period.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] They founded several kingdoms of the Heptarchy in Anglo-Saxon England.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] Their name, which probably derives from the Angeln peninsula, is the root of the names *England* ("Engla land", "Land of the Angles"), and *English*, for both its people and its language.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] According to Tacitus, writing around 100 AD, a people known as Angles (Anglii) lived beyond (apparently northeast of) the Langobards and Semnones, who lived near the River Elbe.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] The name of the Angles may have been first recorded in Latinised form, as *Anglii*, in the *Germania* of Tacitus.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] It is thought to derive from the name of the area they originally inhabited, the Angeln peninsula, which is on the Baltic Sea coast of Schleswig-Holstein.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] The name derives from "hook" (as in angling for fish), in reference to the shape of the peninsula where they lived; Indo-European linguist Julius Pokorny derives it from Proto-Indo-European **h₂enk-*, "bend" (see ankle).
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] Alternatively, the Angles may have been called such because they were a fishing people or were originally descended from such.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] In Old English, the same term *Engle* refers the Angles before and after the migration to Britain.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] As most Germanic settlers in Britain during this time were Angles, the settled area became referred to as England ("Engla land", "the land or country of the Angles").
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] While Latin and Celtic-speaking populations referred to the Germanic speakers in Britain in general by terms related to "Saxons", they came to refer to themselves as *Engle* ("Angles", "English people").
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] "Angle" and related terms therefore have some ambiguity in their scope.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] From *Engle* is also derived "English" (Old English: *Englisc*).
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] According to *Gesta Danorum*, the brothers Dan and Angul were made rulers by the consent of their people because of their bravery and the Danes and Angles are respectively named from them.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] The earliest surviving mention of the Angles is in chapter 40 of Tacitus's *Germania* written around AD 98.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] Tacitus describes the "Anglii" as one of the more remote Suebic tribes living beyond the Semnones and Langobardi, who lived near the lower Elbe, and were better known to the Romans.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] He grouped the Angles with several other tribes in that region, the Reudigni, Aviones, Varini, Eudoses, Suarines, and Nuithones.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] According to Tacitus, they were all living behind ramparts of rivers and woods, and therefore inaccessible to attack.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] He gives no precise indication of their geographical situation but states that, together with the six other tribes, they worshipped Nerthus, or Mother Earth, whose sanctuary was located on "an island in the Ocean".
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] The Eudoses are generally considered to be the Jutes and these names have been associated with localities in Jutland or on the Baltic coast.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] The coast contains sufficient estuaries, inlets, rivers, islands, swamps, and marshes to have been inaccessible to those not familiar with the terrain, such as the Romans, who considered it unknown and inaccessible.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] The majority of scholars believe that the Anglii lived on the coasts of the Baltic Sea, probably in the southern part of the Jutland peninsula.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] This view is based partly on Old English and Danish traditions regarding persons and events of the fourth century, and partly because striking affinities to the cult of Nerthus as described by Tacitus are to be found in pre-Christian Scandinavian religion.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] Surviving versions of the work of Ptolemy, who wrote around AD 150, in his *Geography* (2.10), describe the Angles in a confusing manner.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] This positioning of the Langobardi and Angli is unexpected, as are the positions of many of the peoples in this passage.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] The text is believed to result from the combining of different types of older texts.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] As pointed out by Gudmund Schütte, the neighbouring Langobards appear in two places, and the ones near the Rhine appears to be there by mistake.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] Schütte, in his analysis, believes that the Angles are placed correctly relative to the Langobardi to their west, but that these have been positioned in the wrong place.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] The Langobardi also appear in the expected position on the lower Elbe, and the Angles would be expected to their northeast, based upon Tacitus.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] An especially early reference to the Angli in Britain is by the 6th-century Byzantine historian Procopius (who however expressed doubts about the stories he had heard—apparently from Frankish diplomats—about events in the west).
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] He does not mention the Saxons, but he states that an island called *Brittia* (which he says is separate and distinct from Britain itself) was settled by three nations, each ruled by its own king: the Angili, Frissones, and Brittones.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] According to the digression of Procopius about the Angli, the Warnian king Hermegisclus made a strategic alliance with the Frankish ruler of the neighbouring kingdom of Theudebert I (ruler Austrasia 533-547), marrying his sister Theudechild.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] However, in contrast he had engaged his son with the sister of the Anglian ruler who ruled on Brittia.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] Before his death he expressed the wish to have his son married to his stepmother Theudechild instead.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] As a result when king Hermegisclus died, the Warini compelled his son Radigis to marry his stepmother.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] The princess, who is not named in the story, did not accept this, and crossed the North Sea with an army of 400 ships and 100,000 men, seeking retaliation.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] After a battle won by the Anglians, Radigis was caught hiding in a wood not far from the mouth of the Rhine and had no other choice than to marry his fiancée.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] Bede (died 735) stated that the Anglii, before coming to Great Britain, dwelt in a land called Angulus, "which lies between the province of the Jutes and the Saxons, and remains unpopulated to this day." A similar account, possibly based on Bede's, is given by the 9th-century *Historia Brittonum*.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] King Alfred the Great (died 899) also summarized an account by a Norwegian seafarer Ohthere of Hålogaland who described a voyage from Norway to Hedeby which he said lay between the Wends, Saxons and Angles.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] On the two days sailing south before he reached Hedeby the lands on his right were Jutland ("*Gotland*"), Zealand ("*Sillende*"), and many islands.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] The text notes that the "Engle" had lived "on these lands" (Jutland, Zealand and the islands) before they came to England.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] In Alfred's general geographical section he notes "*Ongle*", "*Sillende*", and a part of the Danish land, as all being to the "northwest" of the continental "Old Saxons" where their lands extended northwards, east of the mouth of the Elbe.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] (To the north and northeast of these Saxons were various Slavic peoples, with the most northerly being the Obotrites ("*Afdrede*").) A later part of the same passage simply describes the northern neighbours of these Saxons and Obotrites as all being in the land of the "South Danes".
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] Confirmation is afforded by English and Danish traditions relating to two kings named Wermund and Offa of Angel, from whom the Mercian royal family claimed descent and whose exploits are connected with Angeln, Schleswig, and Rendsburg.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] Danish tradition has preserved record of two governors of Schleswig, father and son, in their service, Frowinus (Freawine) and Wigo (Wig), from whom the royal family of Wessex claimed descent.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] During the fifth century, the Anglii invaded Great Britain, after which time their name does not recur on the continent except in the title of the legal code issued to the Thuringians: *Lex Angliorum et Werinorum hoc est Thuringorum*.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] The Angles are the subject of a legend about Pope Gregory I (died 604), who happened to see a group of Angle children from Deira for sale as slaves in the Roman market.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] As the story was told by Bede, Gregory was struck by the unusual appearance of the slaves and asked about their background.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] Supposedly, this encounter inspired the pope to launch a mission to bring Christianity to their countrymen.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] The province of Schleswig has proved rich in prehistoric antiquities that date apparently from the fourth and fifth centuries.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] A large cremation cemetery has been found at Borgstedt, between Rendsburg and Eckernförde, and it has yielded many urns and brooches closely resembling those found in pagan graves in England.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] Of still greater importance are the great deposits at Thorsberg moor (in Angeln) and Nydam, which contained large quantities of arms, ornaments, articles of clothing, agricultural implements, etc., and in Nydam, even ships.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] By the help of these discoveries, Angle culture in the age preceding the migration into Britannia can be pieced together.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] According to sources such as the *History* of Bede, after the invasion of Britannia, the Angles split up and founded the kingdoms of Northumbria, East Anglia, and Mercia.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] Loyn has observed in this context that "a sea voyage is perilous to tribal institutions", and the apparently tribe-based kingdoms were formed in England.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] Early times had two northern kingdoms (Bernicia and Deira) and two midland ones (Middle Anglia and Mercia), which had by the seventh century resolved themselves into two Angle kingdoms, viz., Northumbria and Mercia.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] Northumbria held suzerainty amidst the Germanic presence in the British Isles in the 7th century, but was eclipsed by the rise of Mercia in the 8th century.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] Both kingdoms fell in the great assaults of the Danish Viking armies in the 9th century.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] Their royal houses were effectively destroyed in the fighting, and their Angle populations came under the Danelaw.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] Further south, the Saxon kings of Wessex withstood the Danish assaults.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] Then in the late 9th and early 10th centuries, the kings of Wessex defeated the Danes and took control of areas inhabited by Angles that were formerly in the Danelaw.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] They united their house in marriage with the surviving Angle royalty and were accepted by the Angles as their kings, ultimately resulting in the Kingdom of England.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] The regions of East Anglia and Northumbria are still known by their original titles.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] Northumbria once stretched as far north as what is now southeast Scotland, including Edinburgh, and as far south as the Humber Estuary and even the River Witham.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] The rest of that people stayed at the centre of the Angle homeland in the northeastern portion of the modern German *Bundesland* of Schleswig-Holstein, on the Jutland Peninsula.
[src:bernicia/angles-tribe] There, a small peninsular area is still called Angeln today and is formed as a triangle drawn roughly from modern Flensburg on the Flensburger Fjord to the City of Schleswig and then to Maasholm, on the Schlei inlet.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The ***Anglo-Saxon Chronicle*** (also *ASC* and the *Chronicle*) is the term used by historians to describe a set of annals in Old English, chronicling the history of the Anglo-Saxons.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The lost first version of the *Chronicle* was created in the late ninth century, probably in Wessex, during the reign of King Alfred the Great (r.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Its content, which incorporated sources now otherwise lost dating from as early as the seventh century, is known as the "Common Stock" of the *Chronicle*.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Multiple copies were made of that one original and then distributed to monasteries across England, where they were updated, partly independently.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] These manuscripts collectively are known as the *Anglo-Saxon Chronicle*.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Almost all of the material in the *Chronicle* is in the form of annals, by year.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The earliest is dated at 60 BC, the annals' date for Julius Caesar's invasions of Britain.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] In one case, the *Chronicle* was still being actively updated in 1154.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Nine manuscripts of the *Chronicle*, none of which is the original, survive in whole or in part.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Seven are held in the British Library, one in the Bodleian Library at Oxford, and the oldest in the Parker Library of Corpus Christi College, Cambridge.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The oldest seems to have been started towards the end of Alfred's reign, while the most recent was copied at Peterborough Abbey after a fire at that monastery in 1116.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Some later medieval chronicles deriving from lost manuscripts contribute occasional further hints concerning *Chronicle* material.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The *Chronicle*'s accounts tend to be highly politicised, with the Common Stock intended primarily to legitimise the House of Wessex and the reign of Alfred the Great.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Comparison between *Chronicle* manuscripts and with other medieval sources demonstrates that the scribes who copied or added to them omitted events or told one-sided versions of them, often providing useful insights into early medieval English politics.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The Common Stock of the *Chronicle* dates to around 893, as it covers the Vikings' return from the Continent in that year, and a version was available to Bishop Asser for his 893 *Life of King Alfred*).
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] There is debate about precisely which year, and when subsequent continuations began to be added.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] It is not known for certain where the Common Stock was compiled, not least because the archetype is lost, but it is agreed to have been in Wessex.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] It was probably produced in the scholarly circle around King Alfred, He may not have been personally involved, and Simon Keynes and Michael Lapidge comment that we should "resist the temptation to regard it as a form of West Saxon dynastic propaganda".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Yet there is no doubt that the Common Stock systematically promotes Alfred's dynasty and rule, and was consistent with his enthusiasm for learning and the use of English as a written language.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] It seems partly to have been inspired by the Royal Frankish Annals, and its wide distribution is also consistent with Alfredian policies.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Its publication was perhaps prompted by renewed Scandinavian attacks on Wessex.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The Common Stock incorporates material from multiple sources, including annals relating to Kentish, South Saxon, Mercian and, particularly, West Saxon history.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] It is unclear how far this material was first drawn together by the editor(s) of the Common Stock and how far it had already been combined before the late ninth century: there are no obvious shifts in language features in the Common Stock that could help indicate different sources.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Where the Common Stock draws on other known sources its main value to modern historians is as an index of the works and themes that were important to its compilers; where it offers unique material it is of especial historical interest.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] From the first annal, for 60BC, down to 449, the Common Stock mostly presents key events from beyond Britain, a body of material known as the "world history annals".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] These drew on Jerome's *De Viris Illustribus*, the *Liber Pontificalis*, the translation of Eusebius's *Ecclesiastical History* by Rufinus, and Isidore of Seville's *Chronicon*.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Alongside these, down to the early eighth century, the Common Stock makes extensive use of the chronological summary from the end of Bede's *Ecclesiastical History* (and perhaps occasionally the *History* itself).
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Scholars have read these annals as functioning to present England as part of the Roman and Christian world and its history.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] From 449, coverage of non-British history largely vanishes and extensive material about the parts of England which by the ninth century were in Wessex, often unique to the *Chronicle*, appears.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The *Chronicle* offers an ostensibly coherent account of the Anglo-Saxon settlement of southern Britain by seafarers who, through a series of battles, establish the kingdoms of Kent, Sussex, and Wessex.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] This material was once supposed by many historians to be reliable evidence, and formed the backbone of a canonical narrative of early English history; but its unreliability was exposed in the 1980s.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The earliest non-Bedan material here seems to be based primarily on royal genealogies and lists of bishops that were perhaps first being put into writing around 600, as English kings converted to Christianity, and more certainly by the end of the reign of Ine of Wessex (r.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Such sources are best represented by the Anglian King-list and the probably derived West Saxon Genealogical Regnal List.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Detailed comparison of these sources with the Common Stock has helped to show the degree of invention in the Common Stock's vision of the fifth and sixth centuries.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] For example, perhaps due to edits in intermediary annals, the beginning of the reign of Cerdic, supposedly the founder of the West-Saxon dynasty, seems to have been pushed back from 538AD in the earliest reconstructable version of the List to 500AD in the Common Stock.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] At times, invention, usually through folk-etymological origin-myths based on place-names, is even more obvious.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] For example, between 514 and 544 the *Chronicle* makes reference to Wihtgar, who was supposedly buried on the Isle of Wight at *Wihtgaræsbyrg* ("Wihtgar's stronghold") and gave his name to the island.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] However, the name of the Isle of Wight derives from the Latin *Vectis*, not from *Wihtgar*.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The actual name of the fortress was probably *Wihtwarabyrg* ("the stronghold of the inhabitants of Wight"), and either the Common Stock editor(s) or an earlier source misinterpreted this as referring to Wihtgar.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The annal for 648 may mark the point after which entries that were written as a contemporary record begin to appear, and the annal for 661 records a battle fought by Cenwalh that is said to have been fought "at Easter", a precision which implies a contemporary record.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Similar but separate sources would explain the dates and genealogies for Northumbrian and Mercian kings.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The entry for 755, describing how Cynewulf took the kingship of Wessex from Sigeberht, is far longer than the surrounding entries, and includes direct speech quotations from the participants in those events.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] It seems likely that this was taken by the scribe from existing saga material.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] From the late eighth century onwards, a period coinciding in the text with the beginning of Scandinavian raids on England, the *Chronicle* gathered momentum.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] As the *Chronicle* proceeded, it lost its list-like appearance, and annals became longer and more narrative in content.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Many later entries contain a great deal of historical narrative in each annal.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] After the original *Chronicle* was compiled, copies were made and distributed to various monasteries.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Additional copies were made, for further distribution or to replace lost manuscripts, and some copies were updated independently of each other.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] It is copies of this sort that constitute the surviving *Chronicle* manuscripts.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The manuscripts were produced in different places, and at times adaptations made to the Common Stock in the course of copying reflect the agendas of the copyists, providing valuable alternative perspectives.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] These colour both the description of interactions between Wessex and other kingdoms, and the descriptions of the Vikings' depredations.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] For example, the *Chronicle's* annal for 829 describes Egbert's invasion of Northumbria with the comment that the Northumbrians offered him "submission and peace".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Similar divergences are apparent in how different manuscripts of the *Chronicle*.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] For example, Ælfgar, earl of East Anglia, and son of Leofric, the earl of Mercia, was exiled briefly in 1055.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The 1055 campaign involving Ælfgar and Welsh King Gruffudd ap Llywelyn, as recorded in manuscripts [C], [D], and [E], offers examples of how scribes shaped narratives to align with regional or political agendas.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Besides [C] emphasizing Ælfgar's innocence, his collaboration with Gruffudd, who is portrayed as a key ally and titled as a Welsh king, is also extensively mentioned.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Conversely, [E] omits Gruffudd's title and focuses on Ælfgar's alleged treachery, framing both figures as aggressors in the Hereford campaign.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Cardiff University historian Rebecca Thomas states this ideological framing aligns with [E]'s broader "pro-Godwine" perspective (referring to the Anglo-Saxon Godwine family dynasty to whom King Harold II belonged).
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Meanwhile, [D] minimizes details of Gruffudd's involvement in the campaign, offering a more subdued account that excludes his royal title and reduces his role to a supporting figure.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Scribes might also omit material, sometimes accidentally, but also for ideological reasons. Ælfgar was Earl of Mercia by 1058, and in that year was exiled again.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] This time only [D] has anything to say: "Here Earl Ælfgar was expelled, but he soon came back again, with violence, through the help of Gruffydd.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] And here came a raiding ship-army from Norway; it is tedious to tell how it all happened." In this case other sources exist to clarify the picture: a major Norwegian attempt was made on England, but [E] says nothing at all, and [D] scarcely mentions it.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] It has sometimes been argued that when the *Chronicle* is silent, other sources that report major events must be mistaken, but this example demonstrates that the *Chronicle* does omit important events.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The process of manual copying introduced accidental errors in dates; such errors were sometimes compounded in the chain of transmission.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The whole of the Common Stock has a chronological dislocation of two years for the period 756–845 due to two years being missed out in the archetype.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] In the [D] manuscript, the scribe omits the year 1044 from the list on the left-hand side.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The annals copied down are therefore incorrect from 1045 to 1052, which has two entries.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] A more difficult problem is the question of the date at which a new year began, since the modern custom of starting the year on 1 January was not universal at that time.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The entry for 1091 in [E] begins at Christmas and continues throughout the year; it is clear that this entry follows the old custom of starting the year at Christmas.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Some other entries appear to begin the year on 25 March, such as the year 1044 in the [C] manuscript, which ends with Edward the Confessor's marriage on 23 January, while the entry for 22 April is recorded under 1045.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] There are also years which appear to start in September.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Of the nine surviving manuscripts, seven are written entirely in Old English (also known as Anglo-Saxon).
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] One, known as the *Bilingual Canterbury Epitome*, is in Old English with a translation of each annal into Latin.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Another, the *Peterborough Chronicle*, is in Old English except for the last entry, which is in early Middle English.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] MS 173) is known as the *Winchester Chronicle* or the *Parker Chronicle* (after Matthew Parker, an Archbishop of Canterbury, who once owned it), and is written in Old English until 1070, then Latin to 1075.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Six of the manuscripts were printed in an 1861 edition for the Rolls Series by Benjamin Thorpe with the text laid out in columns labelled A to F.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] He also included the few readable remnants of a burned seventh manuscript, which he referred to as [G], partially destroyed in a fire at Ashburnham House in London in 1731, and only a few leaves remain.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Following this convention, the two additional manuscripts are often called [H] and [I].
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The manuscripts are all thought to derive from a common original, but the connections between the texts are more complex than simple inheritance via copying.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The diagram at right gives an overview of the relationships between the manuscripts.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The following is a summary of the relationships that are known.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Hence the error and the missing sentence must have been introduced in separate copying steps, implying that none of the surviving manuscripts are closer than two removes from the original version.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The *Winchester* (or *Parker*) *Chronicle* is the oldest manuscript of the *Chronicle* that survives.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] It was begun at Old Minster, Winchester, towards the end of Alfred's reign.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The manuscript begins with a genealogy of Alfred, and the first chronicle entry is for the year 60 BC.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The section containing the *Chronicle* takes up folios 1–32.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Unlike the other manuscripts, [A] is of early enough composition to show entries dating back to the late 9th century in the hands of different scribes as the entries were made.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The first scribe's hand is dateable to the late 9th or very early 10th century; his entries cease in late 891, and the following entries were made at intervals throughout the 10th century by several scribes.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The eighth scribe wrote the annals for the years 925–955, and was clearly at Winchester when he wrote them since he adds some material related to events there; he also uses *ceaster*, or "city", to mean Winchester.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The manuscript becomes independent of the other recensions after the entry for 975.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The book, which also had a copy of the Laws of Alfred and Ine bound in after the entry for 924, was transferred to Canterbury some time in the early 11th century, as evidenced by a list of books that Archbishop Parker gave to Corpus Christi.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] While at Canterbury, some interpolations were made; this required some erasures in the manuscript.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The additional entries appear to have been taken from a version of the manuscript from which [E] descends.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The last entry in the vernacular is for 1070.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] After this comes the Latin *Acta Lanfranci*, which covers church events from 1070 to 1093.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] This is followed by a list of popes and the Archbishops of Canterbury to whom they sent the pallium.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The manuscript was acquired by Matthew Parker, Archbishop of Canterbury (1559–1575) and is in the collection of the Parker Library, Corpus Christi College.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The *Abingdon Chronicle I* was written by a single scribe in the second half of the 10th century.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] It begins with an entry for 60 BC and ends with the entry for 977.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] A manuscript that is now separate (British Library MS.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] 178) was originally the introduction to this chronicle; it contains a genealogy, as does [A], but extends it to the late 10th century. [B] was at Abingdon in the mid-11th century, because it was used in the composition of [C].
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Shortly after this it went to Canterbury, where interpolations and corrections were made.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] As with [A], it ends with a list of popes and the archbishops of Canterbury to whom they sent the pallium.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Then follows a copy of the chronicle, beginning with 60 BC; the first scribe copied up to the entry for 490, and a second scribe took over up to the entry for 1048.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] [B] and [C] are identical between 491 and 652, but differences thereafter make it clear that the second scribe was also using another copy of the *Chronicle*.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] This scribe also inserted, after the annal for 915, the *Mercian Register*, which covers the years 902–924, and which focuses on Æthelflæd.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The manuscript continues to 1066 and stops in the middle of the description of the Battle of Stamford Bridge.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] In the 12th century a few lines were added to complete the account.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The *Worcester Chronicle* appears to have been written in the middle of the 11th century.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] After 1033 it includes some records from Worcester, so it is generally thought to have been composed there.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Five different scribes can be identified for the entries up to 1054, after which it appears to have been worked on at intervals.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The text includes material from Bede's *Ecclesiastical History* and from a set of 8th-century Northumbrian annals.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] It is thought that some of the entries may have been composed by Archbishop Wulfstan.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] [D] contains more information than other manuscripts on northern and Scottish affairs, and it has been speculated that it was a copy intended for the Anglicised Scottish court.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] From 972 to 1016, the sees of York and Worcester were both held by the same person—Oswald from 972, Ealdwulf from 992, and Wulfstan from 1003, and this may explain why a northern recension was to be found at Worcester.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] By the 16th century, parts of the manuscript were lost; eighteen pages were inserted containing substitute entries from other sources, including [A], [B], [C] and [E].
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] These pages were written by John Joscelyn, who was secretary to Matthew Parker.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The *Peterborough Chronicle*: In 1116, a fire at the monastery at Peterborough destroyed most of the buildings.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The copy of the *Chronicle* kept there may have been lost at that time or later, but in either case shortly thereafter a fresh copy was made, apparently copied from a Kentish version—most likely to have been from Canterbury.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The manuscript was written at one time and by a single scribe, down to the annal for 1121.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The scribe added material relating to Peterborough Abbey which is not in other versions.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The Canterbury original which he copied was similar, but not identical, to [D]: the Mercian Register does not appear, and a poem about the Battle of Brunanburh in 937, which appears in most of the other surviving copies of the *Chronicle*, is not recorded.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The same scribe then continued the annals through to 1131; these entries were made at intervals, and thus are presumably contemporary records.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] A second scribe, in 1154, wrote an account of the years 1132–1154, though his dating is known to be unreliable.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] This last entry is in Middle English, rather than Old English. [E] was once owned by William Laud, Archbishop of Canterbury 1633–1645, so is also known as the *Laud Chronicle*.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The manuscript contains occasional glosses in Latin, and is referred to (as "the Saxon storye of Peterborowe church") in an antiquarian book from 1566.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] According to Joscelyn, Nowell had a transcript of the manuscript.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Previous owners include William Camden and William L'Isle; the latter probably passed the manuscript on to Laud.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The *Canterbury Bilingual Epitome* (London, British Library, Cotton Domitian A.viii, folios 30-70): In about 1100, a copy of the *Chronicle* was written at Christ Church, Canterbury, probably by one of the scribes who made notes in [A].
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] This version is written in both Old English and Latin; each entry in Old English was followed by the Latin version.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The version the scribe copied (on folios 30–70) is similar to the version used by the scribe in Peterborough who wrote [E], though it seems to have been abridged.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] It includes the same introductory material as [D] and, along with [E], is one of the two chronicles that does not include the "Battle of Brunanburh" poem.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The manuscript has many annotations and interlineations, some made by the original scribe and some by later scribes, including Robert Talbot.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Copy of the *Winchester Chronicle*: [A2] was copied from [A] at Winchester in the eleventh century and follows a 10th-century copy of an Old English translation of Bede's *Ecclesiastical History*.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The last annal copied was 1001, so the copy was made no earlier than that; an episcopal list appended to [A2] suggests that the copy was made by 1013.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] This manuscript was almost completely destroyed in the 1731 fire at Ashburnham House in Westminster, where the Cotton Library was housed.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Of the original 34 leaves, seven remain, ff.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] 178), rather than that originally part of this document.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The original [A2] introduction was later removed prior to the fire and survives as British Library Add MS 34652, f.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The appellations [A], [A2] and [G] derive from Plummer, Smith and Thorpe, respectively.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The *Cottonian Fragment* [H] consists of a single leaf, containing annals for 1113 and 1114.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] In the entry for 1113 it includes the phrase "he came to Winchester"; hence it is thought likely that the manuscript was written at Winchester.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] There is not enough of this manuscript for reliable relationships to other manuscripts to be established.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Ker notes that the entries may have been written contemporarily.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Part of [I] was written by a scribe soon after 1073, in the same hand and ink as the rest of the Caligula MS.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] After 1085, the annals are in various contemporary hands.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Two manuscripts are recorded in an old catalogue of the library of Durham; they are described as *cronica duo Anglica*.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] In addition, Parker included a manuscript called *Hist.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Angliae Saxonica* in his gifts but the manuscript that included this, now Cambridge University Library MS.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Hh.1.10, has lost 52 of its leaves, including all of this copy of the chronicle.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The three main Anglo-Norman historians, John of Worcester, William of Malmesbury and Henry of Huntingdon, each had a copy of the *Chronicle*, which they adapted for their own purposes.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Symeon of Durham also had a copy of the *Chronicle*.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Some later medieval historians also used the *Chronicle*, and others took their material from those who had used it, and so the *Chronicle* became "central to the mainstream of English historical tradition".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Henry of Huntingdon used a copy of the *Chronicle* that was very similar to [E].
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Henry also made use of the [C] manuscript.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The Waverley Annals made use of a manuscript that was similar to [E], though it appears that it did not contain the entries focused on Peterborough.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The manuscript of the chronicle translated by Geoffrey Gaimar cannot be identified accurately, though according to historian Dorothy Whitelock it was "a rather better text than 'E' or 'F'".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Gaimar implies that there was a copy at Winchester in his day (the middle of the 12th century); Whitelock suggests that there is evidence that a manuscript that has not survived to the present day was at Winchester in the mid-tenth century.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] John of Worcester's *Chronicon ex chronicis* appears to have had a manuscript that was either [A] or similar to it; he makes use of annals that do not appear in other versions, such as entries concerning Edward the Elder's campaigns and information about Winchester towards the end of the chronicle.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] His account is often similar to that of [D], though there is less attention paid to Margaret of Scotland, an identifying characteristic of [D].
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] He had the Mercian register, which appears only in [C] and [D]; and he includes material from annals 979–982 which only appears in [C].
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] It is possible he had a manuscript that was an ancestor of [D].
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] He also had sources which have not been identified, and some of his statements have no earlier surviving source.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] It is likely he had either the original from which [E] was copied, or a copy of that original.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] He mentions that the chronicles do not give any information on the murder of Alfred Aetheling, but since this is covered in both [C] and [D] it is apparent he had no access to those manuscripts.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] On occasion he appears to show some knowledge of [D], but it is possible that his information was taken from John of Worcester's account.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] He also omits any reference to a battle fought by Cenwealh in 652; this battle is mentioned in [A], [B] and [C], but not in [E].
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] He does mention a battle fought by Cenwealh at Wirtgernesburg, which is not in any of the extant manuscripts, so it is possible he had a copy now lost.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] One early edition of the *Chronicle* was Abraham Wheelocke's 1644 *Venerabilis Bedae Historia Ecclesiastica*, printed in Cambridge and based on manuscript G.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] An important edition appeared in 1692, by Edmund Gibson, an English jurist and divine who later (1716) became Bishop of Lincoln.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Titled *Chronicon Saxonicum*, it printed the Old English text in parallel columns with Gibson's own Latin version and became the standard edition until the 19th century.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Gibson used three manuscripts of which the chief was the *Peterborough Chronicle*.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] It was superseded in 1861 by Benjamin Thorpe's Rolls Series edition, which printed six versions in columns, labelled A to F, thus giving the manuscripts the letters which are now used to refer to them.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] John Earle edited *Two of the Saxon Chronicles Parallel* in 1865.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Charles Plummer revised this edition, providing notes, appendices, and glossary in two volumes in 1892 and 1899.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] This edition of the A and E texts, with material from other versions, was widely used; it was reprinted in 1952.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The standard modern English translations are by Dorothy Whitelock, David Douglas and Susie Tucker, and by Michael Swanton.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Rositzke published a translation of the [E] text in *The Peterborough Chronicle* (New York, 1951).
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] An edition and facing-page modern English translation of the [A] text appears in Janet Bately, Joseph C.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Harris, and Katherine O'Brien O'Keeffe, with Susan Irvine, *The Old English Chronicle, Volume I: The A-Text to 1001 and Related Poems,* Dumbarton Oaks Medieval Library 91 (Cambridge, MA, 2025).
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Beginning in the 1980s, a set of scholarly editions of the text in Old English has been printed under the series title "The Anglo-Saxon Chronicle: A Collaborative Edition".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Brewer under the general editorship of David Dumville and Simon Keynes.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The Collaborative Edition did not include MS G because an edition by Angelika Lutz, described by Pauline Stafford as "excellent", had recently been published.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Other modern scholarly editions of different *Chronicle* manuscripts are as follows.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] The [C] manuscript has been edited by H.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Rositzke as "The C-Text of the Old English Chronicles", in *Beiträge zur Englischen Philologie*, XXXIV, Bochum-Langendreer, 1940.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] A scholarly edition of the [D] manuscript is in *An Anglo-Saxon Chronicle from British Museum Cotton MS., Tiberius B. iv*, edited by E.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] Magoun, Jr., *Annales Domitiani Latini: an Edition* in "Mediaeval Studies of the Pontifical Institute of Mediaeval Studies", IX, 1947, pp.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-chronicle] An earlier facsimile edition of [A], *The Parker Chronicle and Laws*, appeared in 1941 from Oxford University Press, edited by Robin Flower and Hugh Smith.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Contemporary knowledge of Anglo-Saxon paganism derives largely from three sources: textual evidence produced by Christian Anglo-Saxons like Bede and Aldhelm, place-name evidence, and archaeological evidence of cultic practices.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Further suggestions regarding the nature of Anglo-Saxon paganism have been developed through comparisons with the better-attested pre-Christian belief systems of neighbouring peoples such as the Norse.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Anglo-Saxon paganism was a polytheistic belief system, focused around a belief in deities known as the *ése* (singular *ós*).
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The most prominent of these deities was probably Woden; other prominent gods included Thunor and Tiw.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] There was also a belief in a variety of other supernatural entities which inhabited the landscape, including elves, nicors, and dragons.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Cultic practice largely revolved around demonstrations of devotion, including sacrifice of inanimate objects and animals to these deities, particularly at certain religious festivals during the year.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] There is some evidence for the existence of timber temples, although other cultic spaces might have been open-air, and would have included cultic trees and megaliths.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Little is known about pagan conceptions of an afterlife, although such beliefs likely influenced funerary practices, in which the dead were either interred or cremated, typically with a selection of grave goods.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The belief system also likely included ideas about magic and witchcraft, and elements that could be classified as a form of shamanism.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The deities of this religion provided the basis for the names of the days of the week in the English language.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] What is known about the religion and its accompanying mythology have since influenced both literature and modern paganism.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The word *pagan* is a Latin pejorative term that was used by Gentile Christianity (also: *Pagan Christianity*) in Anglo-Saxon England to designate non-Christians.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] In Old English, the vernacular language of Anglo-Saxon England, the equivalent term was *hæðen* ("heathen"), a word that was cognate to the Old Norse *heiðinn*, both of which may derive from a Gothic word, *haiþno*.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Both *pagan* and *heathen* were terms that carried pejorative overtones, with *hæðen* also being used in Late Anglo-Saxon texts to refer to criminals and others deemed to have not behaved according to Christian teachings.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The term "paganism" was one used by Gentile Christians as a form of othering, and as the archaeologist Neil Price put it, in the Anglo-Saxon context, "paganism" is "largely an empty concept defined by what it is not (Christianity)".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] There is no evidence that anyone living in Anglo-Saxon England ever described themselves as a "pagan" or understood there to be a singular religion, "paganism", that stood as a monolithic alternative to Christianity.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] These pagan belief systems would have been inseparable from other aspects of daily life.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] As a phenomenon, this belief system lacked any apparent rules or consistency, and exhibited both regional and chronological variation.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The archaeologist Aleks Pluskowski suggested that it is possible to talk of "multiple Anglo-Saxon 'paganisms'".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Also adopting the categories of Gustav Mensching, she described Anglo-Saxon paganism as a "folk religion", in that its adherents concentrated on survival and prosperity in this world.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Using the expressions "paganism" or "heathenism" when discussing pre-Christian belief systems in Anglo-Saxon England is problematic.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Historically, many early scholars of the Anglo-Saxon period used these terms to describe the religious beliefs in England before its conversion to Christianity in the 7th century.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Several later scholars criticised this approach; as the historian Ian N.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Wood stated, using the term "pagan" when discussing the Anglo-Saxons forces the scholar to adopt "the cultural constructs and value judgements of the early medieval [Christian] missionaries" and thus obscures scholarly understandings of the so-called pagans' own perspectives.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] At present, while some Anglo-Saxonists have ceased using the terms "paganism" or "pagan" when discussing the early Anglo-Saxon period, others have continued to do so, viewing these terms as a useful means of designating something that is not Christian yet which is still identifiably religious.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The historian John Hines proposed "traditional religion" as a better alternative, although Carver cautioned against this, noting that Britain in the 5th to the 8th century was replete with new ideas and thus belief systems of that period were not particularly "traditional".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The term "pre-Christian" religion has also been used; this avoids the judgemental connotations of "paganism" and "heathenism" but is not always chronologically accurate.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Surviving primary textual source material derives from later authors, such as Bede and the anonymous author of the *Life of St Wilfrid*, who wrote in Latin rather than in Old English.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] These writers were not interested in providing a full portrait of the Anglo-Saxons' pre-Christian belief systems, and thus our textual portrayal of these religious beliefs is fragmentary and incidental.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Far fewer textual records discuss Anglo-Saxon paganism than the pre-Christian belief systems found in nearby Ireland, Francia, or Scandinavia.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] There is no neat, formalised account of Anglo-Saxon pagan beliefs as there is for instance for Classical mythology and Norse mythology.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Although many scholars have used Norse mythology as a guide to understanding the beliefs of pre-Christian Anglo-Saxon England, caution has been expressed as to the utility of this approach.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Conversely, the historian Brian Branston argued for the use of Old Norse sources to better understand Anglo-Saxon pagan beliefs, recognising mythological commonalities between the two rooted in their common ancestry.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Old English place-names also provide some insight into the pre-Christian beliefs and practices of Anglo-Saxon England.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Some of these place-names reference the names of particular deities, while others use terms that refer to cultic practices that took place there.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] In England, these two categories remain separate, unlike in Scandinavia, where certain place-names exhibit both features.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Those place-names which carry possible pagan associations are centred primarily in the centre and south-east of England, while no obvious examples are known from Northumbria or East Anglia.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] It is not clear why such names are rarer or non-existent in certain parts of the country; it may be due to changes in nomenclature brought about by Scandinavian settlement in the Late Anglo-Saxon period or because of evangelising efforts by later Christian authorities.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] In 1941, Stenton suggested that "between fifty and sixty sites of heathen worship" could be identified through the place-name evidence, although in 1961 the place-name scholar Margaret Gelling cautioned that only forty-five of these appeared reliable.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Shaw has however warned that many of these sites might not have been named by pagans but by later Christian Anglo-Saxons, reflecting spaces that were perceived to be heathen from a Christian perspective.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] According to Wilson, the archaeological evidence is "prolific and hence is potentially the most useful in the study of paganism" in Anglo-Saxon England.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Archaeologically, the realms of religion, ritual, and magic can only be identified if they affected material culture.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] As such, scholarly understandings of pre-Christian religion in Anglo-Saxon England are reliant largely on rich burials and monumental buildings, which exert as much of a political purpose as a religious one.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Metalwork items discovered by metal detectorists have also contributed to the interpretation of Anglo-Saxon paganism.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The world-views of the pre-Christian Anglo-Saxons would have impinged on all aspects of everyday life, making it particularly difficult for modern scholars to separate Anglo-Saxon ritual activities as something distinct from other areas of daily life.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Much of this archaeological material comes from the period in which pagan beliefs were being supplanted by Christianity, and thus an understanding of Anglo-Saxon paganism must be seen in tandem with the archaeology of the conversion.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Based on the evidence available, the historian John Blair stated that the pre-Christian religion of Anglo-Saxon England largely resembled "that of the pagan Britons under Roman rule... at least in its outward forms".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] However, the archaeologist Audrey Meaney concluded that there exists "very little undoubted evidence for Anglo-Saxon paganism, and we remain ignorant of many of its essential features of organisation and philosophy".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Similarly, the Old English specialist Roy Page stated that the surviving evidence was "too sparse and too scattered" to permit a good understanding of Anglo-Saxon paganism.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] During most of the fourth century, the majority of Britain had been part of the Roman Empire, which—starting in 380 AD with the Edict of Thessalonica—had Christianity as its official religion.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] However, in Britain, Christianity was probably still a minority religion, restricted largely to the urban centres and their hinterlands.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] While it did have some impact in the countryside, here it appears that indigenous Late Iron Age polytheistic belief systems continued to be widely practised.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Some areas, such as the Welsh Marches, the majority of Wales (excepting Gwent), Lancashire, and the south-western peninsula, are totally lacking evidence for Christianity in this period.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Britons who found themselves in the areas now dominated by Anglo-Saxon elites possibly embraced the Anglo-Saxons' pagan religion in order to aid their own self-advancement, just as they adopted other trappings of Anglo-Saxon culture.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] This would have been easier for those Britons who, rather than being Christian, continued to practise indigenous polytheistic belief systems, and in areas this Late Iron Age polytheism could have syncretically mixed with the incoming Anglo-Saxon religion.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Conversely, there is weak possible evidence for limited survival of Roman Christianity into the Anglo-Saxon period, such as the place-name *ecclēs*, meaning 'church', at two locations in Norfolk and Eccles in Kent.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] However, Blair suggested that Roman Christianity would not have experienced more than a "ghost-life" in Anglo-Saxon areas.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Those Britons who continued to practise Christianity were probably perceived as second-class citizens and were unlikely to have had much of an impact on the pagan kings and aristocracy which was then emphasising Anglo-Saxon culture and defining itself against British culture.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] If the British Christians were able to convert any of the Anglo-Saxon elite conquerors, it was likely only on a small community scale, with British Christianity having little impact on the later establishment of Anglo-Saxon Christianity in the seventh century.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Prior scholarship tended to view Anglo-Saxon paganism as a development from an older Germanic paganism.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The scholar Michael Bintley cautioned against this approach, noting that this "'Germanic' paganism" had "never had a single *ur*-form" from which later variants developed.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Anglo-Saxon paganism only existed for a relatively short time-span, from the fifth to the eighth centuries.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Our knowledge of the Christianisation process derives from Christian textual sources.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Both Latin and ogham inscriptions and the *Ruin of Britain* by Gildas suggest that the leading families of Dumnonia and other Brittonic kingdoms had already adopted Christianity in the 6th century.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] In 596, Pope Gregory I ordered a Gregorian mission to be launched in order to convert the Anglo-Saxons to the Roman Catholic Church.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The leader of this mission, Augustine, probably landed in Thanet, then part of the Kingdom of Kent, in the summer of 597.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] While Christianity was initially restricted to Kent, it saw "major and sustained expansion" in the period from c.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The next phase of the conversion took place between c.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] 653 and 664, and entailed the Northumbrian sponsored conversion of the rulers of the East Saxons, Middle Anglians, and Mercians.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] In the final phase of the conversion, which took place during the 670s and 680s, the final two Anglo-Saxon kingdoms to be led by pagan rulers—in Sussex and the Isle of Wight—saw their leaders baptised.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] As with other areas of Europe, the conversion to Christianity was facilitated by the aristocracy.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] These rulers may have felt themselves to be members of a pagan backwater in contrast to the Christian kingdoms in continental Europe.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The pace of Christian conversion varied across Anglo-Saxon England, with it taking almost 90 years for the official conversion to succeed.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Most of the Anglo-Saxon kingdoms returned to paganism for a time after the death of their first converted king.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] However, by the end of the 680s, all of the Anglo-Saxon peoples were at least nominally Christian.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Blair noted that for most Anglo-Saxons, the "moral and practical imperatives" of following one's lord by converting to Christianity were a "powerful stimulus".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] It remains difficult to determine the extent to which pre-Christian beliefs retained their popularity among the Anglo-Saxon populace from the seventh century onward.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] *Theodore's Penitential* and the Laws of Wihtred of Kent issued in 695 imposed penalties on those who provided offerings to "demons".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] However, by two or three decades later, Bede could write as if paganism had died out in Anglo-Saxon England.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Condemnations of pagan cults also do not appear in other canons from this later period, again suggesting that ecclesiastical figures no longer considered persisting paganism to be a problem.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] In the latter decades of the ninth century during the Late Anglo-Saxon period, Scandinavian settlers arrived in Britain, bringing with them their own, kindred pre-Christian beliefs.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] No cultic sites used by Scandinavian pagans have been archaeologically identified, although place names suggest some possible examples.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] For instance, Roseberry Topping in North Yorkshire was known as Othensberg in the twelfth century, a name which derived from the Old Norse *Óðinsberg*, or 'Hill of Óðin'.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] A number of place-names also contain Old Norse references to mythological entities, such as *alfr*, *skratii*, and *troll*.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] A number of pendants representing Mjolnir, the hammer of the god Thor, have also been found in England, reflecting the probability that he was worshipped among the Anglo-Scandinavian population.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] North however argued that one passage in the Old English rune poem, written in the eighth or ninth century, may reflect knowledge of the Scandinavian god Týr.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Archaeologically, the introduction of Norse paganism to Britain in this period is mostly visited in the mortuary evidence.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] A number of Scandinavian furnished burial styles were also introduced that differed from the Christian churchyard burials then dominant in Late Anglo-Saxon England.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Whether these represent clear pagan identity or not is however debated among archaeologists.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Norse mythological scenes have also been identified on a number of stone carvings from the period, such as the Gosforth Cross, which included images of *Ragnarök*.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The English church found that it needed to conduct a new conversion process to Christianize the incoming Scandinavian population.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] It is not well understood how the Christian institutions converted these settlers, in part due to a lack of textual descriptions of this conversion process equivalent to Bede's description of the earlier Anglo-Saxon conversion.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] However, it appears that the Scandinavian migrants had converted to Christianity within the first few decades of their arrival.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Such "cultural paganism" could represent a reference to the cultural heritage of the Scandinavian population rather than their religious heritage.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] For instance, many Norse mythological themes and motifs are present in the poetry composed for the court of Cnut the Great, an eleventh-century Anglo-Scandinavian king who had been baptised into Christianity and who otherwise emphasised his identity as a Christian monarch.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Although Christianity had been adopted across Anglo-Saxon England by the late seventh century, many pre-Christian customs continued to be practised.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Bintley argued that aspects of Anglo-Saxon paganism served as the foundations for parts of Anglo-Saxon Christianity.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Pre-Christian beliefs affected the folklore of the Anglo-Saxon period, and through this continued to exert an influence on popular religion within the late Anglo-Saxon period.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Blair noted that even in the late eleventh century, "important aspects of lay Christianity were still influenced by traditional indigenous practices".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Both secular and church authorities issued condemnations of alleged non-Christian pagan practices, such as the veneration of wells, trees, and stones, right through to the eleventh century and into the High Middle Ages.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Various scholars, among them historical geographer Della Hooke and Price, have contrastingly believed that these reflected the continuing practice of veneration at wells and trees at a popular level long after the official Christianisation of Anglo-Saxon society.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Various elements of English folklore from the Medieval period onwards have been interpreted as being survivals from Anglo-Saxon paganism.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The Abbots Bromley Horn Dance, which is performed annually in the village of Abbots Bromley in Staffordshire, has also been claimed, by some, to be a remnant of Anglo-Saxon paganism.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The antlers used in the dance belonged to reindeer and have been carbon dated to the eleventh century, and it is therefore believed that they originated in Norway and were brought to England some time in the late Mediaeval period, as by that time reindeer were extinct in Britain.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Little is known about the cosmological beliefs of Anglo-Saxon paganism.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Carver, Sanmark, and Semple suggested that every community within Anglo-Saxon England likely had "its own take on cosmology, although they suggested that there might have been "an underlying system" that was widely shared.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The later Anglo-Saxon *Nine Herbs Charm* mentions seven worlds, which may be a reference to an earlier pagan cosmological belief.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Similarly, Bede claimed that the Christian king Oswald of Northumbria defeated a pagan rival at a sacred plain or meadow called Heavenfield (*Hefenfelth*), which may be a reference to a pagan belief in a heavenly plain.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] He suggested that it was cognate to the Icelandic term Urdr and thus was connected to the concept of three sisters, the Nornir, who oversee fate in recorded Norse mythology.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] It is possible that the pre-Christian Anglo-Saxons held a belief in an apocalypse that bore similarities with the later Norse myth of Ragnarok.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Although no evidence so far directly testifies to the existence of such a belief, the possibility that the pre-Christian Anglo-Saxons believed in a cosmological world tree has also been considered.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] It has been suggested that the idea of a world tree can be discerned through certain references in the *Dream of the Rood* poem.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] This idea may be bolstered if it is the case, as some scholars have argued, that their concept of a world tree may be derived from a purported common Indo-European root.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The historian Clive Tolley has cautioned that any Anglo-Saxon world tree would likely not be directly comparable to that referenced in Norse textual sources.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Anglo-Saxon paganism was a polytheistic belief system, with its practitioners believing in many deities.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] However, most Christian Anglo-Saxon writers had little or no interest in the pagan gods, and thus did not discuss them in their texts.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The Old English words for a god were *ēs* and *ōs*, and they may be reflected in such place-names as Easole ("God's Ridge") in Kent and Eisey ("God's Island") in Wiltshire.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The deity for whom the most evidence exists is Woden, as "traces of his cult are scattered more widely over the rolling English countryside than those of any other heathen deity".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The name Woden also appears as an ancestor of the royal genealogies of Kent, Wessex, East Anglia and Mercia, resulting in suggestions that after losing his status as a god during the Christianisation process he was euhemerised as a royal ancestor.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Woden also appears as the leader of the Wild Hunt, and he is referred to as a magical healer in the *Nine Herbs Charm*, directly paralleling the role of his continental German counterpart Wodan in the Merseburg Incantations.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] He is also often interpreted as being cognate with the Norse god Óðinn and the Old High German Uuodan.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Additionally, he appears in the Old English ancestor of *Wednesday*, Ƿōdenesdæġ ( a calque from its Latin equivalent, as are the rest of the days of the week).
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] It has been suggested that Woden was also known as Grim—a name which appears in such English place-names as Grimspound in Dartmoor, Grimes Graves in Norfolk and Grimsby ("Grim's Village") in Lincolnshire—because in recorded Norse mythology, the god Óðinn is also known as Grímnir.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Highlighting that there are around twice as many *Grim* place-names in England as *Woden* place-names, the place-name scholar Margaret Gelling cautioned against the view that *Grim* was always associated with Woden in Anglo-Saxon England.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The second-most-widespread deity in Anglo-Saxon England appears to be the god Thunor.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] It has been suggested that the hammer and the swastika were the god's symbols, representing thunderbolts, and both of these symbols have been found in Anglo-Saxon graves, the latter being common on cremation urns.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] A large number of Thunor place-names feature the Old English word *lēah* ("wood", or "clearing in a wood"), among them Thunderley and Thundersley in Essex.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The deity's name also appears in other compounds too, as with Thunderfield ("Thunor's Open Land") in Surrey and *Thunores hlaew* ("Thunor's Mound") in Kent.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] A third Anglo-Saxon god that is attested is Tiw.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] In the Anglo-Saxon rune poem, *Tir* is identified with the star Polaris rather than with a deity, although it has been suggested that Tiw was probably a war deity.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Dunn has suggested that Tiw might have been a supreme creator deity who was nevertheless deemed distant.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The name Tiw has been identified in such place-names as Tuesley ("Tiw's Wood or Clearing") in Surrey, Tysoe ("Tiw's Hill-Spur") in Warwickshire, and Tyesmere ("Tiw's Pool") in Worcestershire.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] It has been suggested that the "T"-rune which appears on some weapons and crematory urns from the Anglo-Saxon period may be references to Tiw.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Perhaps the most prominent female deity in Anglo-Saxon paganism was Frig; however, there is still very little evidence for her worship, although it has been speculated that she was "a goddess of love or festivity".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Her name has been suggested as a component of the place-names Fretherne in Gloucestershire, and Freefolk, Frobury, and Froyle in Hampshire.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The East Saxon royalty claimed lineage from someone known as Seaxnēat, who might have been a god, in part because an Old Saxon baptismal vow calls on the Christian to renounce "Thunaer, Woden and Saxnot".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] A runic poem mentions a god known as Ingwine and the writer Asser mentioned a god known as Gēat.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The Christian monk known as the Venerable Bede also mentioned two further goddesses in his written works: Eostre, who was celebrated at a spring festival, and Hretha, whose name meant "glory".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] References to idols can be found in Anglo-Saxon texts.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] No wooden carvings of anthropomorphic figures have been found in the area that once encompassed Anglo-Saxon England that are comparable to those found in Scandinavia or continental Europe.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] It may be that such sculptures were typically made out of wood, which has not survived in the archaeological record.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Several anthropomorphic images have been found, mostly in Kent and dated to the first half of the seventh century; however, identifying these with any particular deity has not proven possible.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] A seated male figure appears on a cremation urn's lid discovered at Spong Hill in Norfolk, which was interpreted as a possible depiction of Woden on a throne.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Also found on many crematory urns are a variety of symbols; of these, the swastikas have sometimes been interpreted as symbols associated with Thunor.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Many Anglo-Saxonists have also assumed that Anglo-Saxon paganism was animistic in basis, believing in a landscape populated by different spirits and other non-human entities, such as elves, dwarves, and dragons.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The English literature scholar Richard North for instance described it as a "natural religion based on animism".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Dunn suggested that for Anglo-Saxon pagans, most everyday interactions would not have been with major deities but with such "lesser supernatural beings".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] She also suggested that these entities might have exhibited similarities with later English beliefs in fairies.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Later Anglo-Saxon texts refer to beliefs in *ælfe* (elves), who are depicted as male but exhibit effeminate traits; these *ælfe* may have been a part of older pagan beliefs.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Various Old English place names reference *þyrsas* (giants) and *dracan* (dragons).
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] However, such names did not necessarily emerge during the pagan period of early Anglo-Saxon England, and could have developed at a later date.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] In pre-Christian Anglo-Saxon England, legends and other stories were transmitted orally instead of being written down; it is for this reason that very few survive today.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] In both *Beowulf* and *Deor's Lament* there are references to the mythological smith Weyland, and this figure also makes an appearance on the Franks Casket.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] There are moreover two place-names recorded in tenth century charters that include Weyland's name.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] This entity's mythological stories are better fleshed out in Norse stories.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The only surviving Anglo-Saxon epic poem is the story of *Beowulf*, known only from a surviving manuscript that was written down by the Christian monk Sepa sometime between the eighth and eleventh centuries AD.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The story it tells is set not in England but in Southern Scandinavia, and revolves around a Geatish warrior named Beowulf who travels to Denmark to defeat a monster known as Grendel, who is terrorising the kingdom of Hrothgar, and later, Grendel's Mother as well.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Following this, he later becomes the king of Geatland before finally dying in battle with a dragon.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] In the eighteenth and early nineteenth centuries, it was commonly believed that *Beowulf* was not an Anglo-Saxon pagan tale, but a Scandinavian Christian one; it was not until the influential critical essay *Beowulf: The Monsters and the Critics* by J.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Tolkien, delivered in 1936, that *Beowulf* was established as a quintessentially English poem that, while Christian, looked back on a living memory of paganism.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] The poem refers to pagan practices such as cremation burials, but also contains repeated mentions of the Christian God and references to tales from Biblical mythology, such as that of Cain and Abel.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p01] Given the restricted nature of literacy in Anglo-Saxon England, it is likely that the author of the poem was a cleric or an associate of the clergy.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Weapons, amongst them spears, swords, seaxes, and shield fittings have been found in English rivers, such as the River Thames, although no large-scale weapons deposits in wetlands have been discovered that are akin to those found elsewhere in Europe.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Place-name evidence may indicate some locations which were used as places of worship by the pre-Christian Anglo-Saxons.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] However, no unambiguous archaeological evidence currently supports the interpretation of these sites as places of cultic practice.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Two words that appear repeatedly in Old English place names *hearg* and *wēoh*, have been interpreted as being references to cult spaces, however it is likely that the two terms had distinctive meanings.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] These *hearg* locations were all found on high ground, with Wilson suggesting that these represented a communal place of worship for a specific group, such as the tribe, at a specific time of year.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The archaeologist Sarah Semple also examined a number of such sites, noting that while they all reflected activity throughout later prehistory and the Romano-British period, they had little evidence from the sixth and seventh centuries CE.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Highlighting that while *wēoh* sites vary in their location, some being on high ground and others on low ground, Wilson noted that the majority were very close to ancient routeways.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Accordingly, he suggested that the term *wēoh* denoted a "small, wayside shrine, accessible to the traveller".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Given that some *wēoh*-sites were connected to the name of an individual, Wilson suggested that such individuals may have been the owner or guardian of the shrine.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] A number of place-names including reference to pre-Christian deities compound these names with the Old English word *lēah* ("wood", or "clearing in a wood"), and this may have attested to a sacred grove at which cultic practice took place.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] A number of other place-names associate the deity's name with a high point in the landscape, such as *dūn* or *hōh*, which might represent that such spots were considered particularly appropriate for cultic practice.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] In six examples, the deity's name is associated with *feld* ("open land"), in which case these might have been sanctuaries located to specifically benefit the agricultural actions of the community.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Some Old English place names make reference to an animal's head, among them Gateshead ("Goat's Head") in Tyne and Wear and Worms Heath ("Snake's Head") in Surrey.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] It is possible that some of these names had pagan religious origins, perhaps referring to a sacrificed animal's head that was erected on a pole, or a carved representation of one; equally some or all of these place-names may have been descriptive metaphors for local landscape features.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] No cultic building has survived from the early Anglo-Saxon period, nor does any contemporary illustration or even a clear description of such a structure.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] However, four references to pre-Christian cultic structures appear in Anglo-Saxon literary sources.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Three of these can be found in Bede's *Ecclesiastical History*.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] One is a quotation from a letter written in 601 by Pope Gregory the Great to the Abbot Mellitus, in which he stated that Christian missionaries need not destroy "the temples of the idols" but that they should be sprinkled with holy water and converted into churches.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] A second reference to cultic spaces found in Bede appears in his discussion of Coifi, an influential English pagan priest for King Edwin of Northumbria, who – after converting to Christianity – cast a spear into the temple at Goodmanham and then burned it to the ground.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The third account was a reference to a temple in which King Rædwald of East Anglia kept an altar to both the Christian God and another to "demons".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Bede referred to these spaces using the Latin term *fanum*; he did not mention whether they were roofed or not, although he chose to use *fanum* over the Latin term *templum*, which would more clearly describe a roofed temple building.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] However, Bede probably never saw a pagan cultic space first hand, and was thus relying on literary sources for his understanding of what they looked like.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Summarising the archaeological evidence, C.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Arnold concluded that "the existence and nature of possible shrines remain intangible at present".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The best known archaeological candidate for a building used in pre-Christian cultic practice is Building D2 at the *Ad Gefrin* royal villa complex at Yeavering in Northumberland.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Blair suggested that the development of temple buildings in the late sixth and seventh centuries reflects the assimilation of Christian ideas.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Other possible temples or shrine buildings have been identified by archaeological investigation as existing within such Anglo-Saxon cemeteries as Lyminge in Kent and Bishopstone in Sussex.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Although Pope Gregory referred to the conversion of pagan cult spaces into churches, no archaeological investigation has yet found any firm evidence of churches being built on top of earlier pagan temples in England.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] It may be that Gregory's advice was never taken by the Anglo-Saxon Christians, although it is possible that the construction of crypts and the rebuilding of churches have destroyed earlier pagan foundations.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Blair highlighted evidence for the existence of square enclosures dating from the early Anglo-Saxon period which often included standing posts and which were often superimposed on earlier prehistoric monuments, most notably Bronze Age barrows.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Building on Blair's argument, the archaeologist Sarah Semple suggested that in Early Anglo-Saxon England such barrows might have been understood as "the home of spirits, ancestors or gods" and accordingly used as cultic places.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] According to Semple "ancient remains in the landscape held a significant place in the Anglo-Saxon mind as part of a wider, numinous, spiritual and resonant landscape".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Blair suggested that the scant archaeological evidence for built cultic structures may be because many cultic spaces in early Anglo-Saxon England did not involve buildings.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Arnold suggested that it may be mistaken to assume that the pre-Christian Anglo-Saxons carried out ritual activity at specific sites, instead suggesting that such practices occurred within the domestic area.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] As evidence, he pointed to certain deposits that have been excavated in Anglo-Saxon settlements, such as the deposition of an adult cow above a pit of clay and cobbles which had been placed at Cowdery's Down.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The deposition of human and animal bone in settlement sites has parallels both with continental practices and with Iron Age and Romano-British practices in Britain.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Although there are virtually no references to pre-Christian sacred trees in Old English literature, there are condemnations of tree veneration as well as the veneration of stones and wells in several later Anglo-Saxon penitentials.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] In the 680s, the Christian writer Aldhelm referred to the pagan use of pillars associated with the "foul snake and stag", praising the fact that many had been converted into sites for Christian worship.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Aldhelm had used the Latin terms *ermula cruda* ("crude pillars"), although it was unclear what exactly he was referring to; possibly examples include something akin to a wooden totem pole or a re-used Neolithic menhir.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Meaney suggested that Aldhelm's reference to the snake and stag might be describing a representation of an animal's head atop a pole, in which case it would be related to the animal-head place-names.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] North also believed that this snake and stag were animals with pagan religious associations.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] It remains difficult to determine the location of any pre-Christian holy trees.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] However, there are cases where sacred trees and groves may be referenced in place-names.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Blair suggested that the use of the Old English word *bēam* ("tree") in Anglo-Saxon place-names may be a reference to a special tree.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] He also suggested that the place-names containing *stapol* ("post" or "pillar") might have represented trees that had been venerated when alive and which were transformed into carved pillars after their death.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] For instance, both Thurstable Hundred in Essex and Thurstaple in Kent appear to have derived from the Old English *Þunres-stapol*, meaning 'Pillar of Þunor'.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Archaeologically, a large post was discovered at Yeavering which has been interpreted as having a religious function.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The purpose of such poles remains debatable, however; some might have represented grave markers, others might have signalised group or kin identities, or marked territory, assembly places, or sacred spaces.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Such wooden pillars would have been easy to convert into large crucifixes following the conversion to Christianity, and thus a number of these sacred sites may have survived as cultic spaces within a Christian context.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] It has also been suggested that the vinescroll patterns that decorated a number of Late Anglo-Saxon stone crosses, such as the Ruthwell Cross, may have been a form of inculturation harking back to pre-Christian tree veneration.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] As Bintley commented, the impact of pre-Christian beliefs about sacred trees on Anglo-Saxon Christian beliefs should be interpreted "not as pagan survivals, but as a fully integrated aspect of early English Christianity".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Christian sources regularly complained that the pagans of Anglo-Saxon England practised animal sacrifice.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] In the seventh century, the first laws against pagan sacrifices appeared, while in the *Paenitentiale Theodori* one to ten years' penance was allotted for making sacrifices or for eating sacrificed meat.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Archaeological evidence reveals that meat was often used as a funerary offering and in many cases whole animal carcasses were placed in burials.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Commenting on this archaeological evidence, Pluskowski stated that this reflected "a regular and well-established practice in early Anglo-Saxon society".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] It appears that they emphasised the killing of oxen over other species, as suggested by both written and archaeological evidence.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Archaeologist David Wilson stated that these may be "evidence of sacrifices to a pagan god".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The folklorist Jacqueline Simpson has suggested that some English folk customs recorded in the late medieval and early modern periods involving the display of a decapitated animal's head on a pole may derive their origins from pre-Christian sacrificial practices.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Unlike some other areas of Germanic Europe, there is no written evidence for human sacrifice being practised in Anglo-Saxon England.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Dunn argued that had Christian writers believed that such practices were being carried out, they would have strongly condemned them.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] But in the view of the historian Hilda Ellis Davidson, "undoubtedly human sacrifice must have been known to the Anglo-Saxons, even if it played no great part in their lives".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] She suggested that victims included slaves, criminals, or prisoners of war, and that such sacrifices were only resorted to in times of crisis, such as plagues, famine, or attack.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Some historians have speculated that twenty-three of the corpses at the Sutton Hoo burial site were sacrificial victims clustered around a sacred tree from which they had been hanged.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The historian Ronald Hutton has suggested that the corpse of an Anglo-Saxon woman found at Sewerby on the Yorkshire Wolds may have been buried alive alongside a nobleman, possibly as a sacrifice, or to accompany him to the afterlife.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Wilson stated that "virtually nothing" was known of the pre-Christian priesthood in Anglo-Saxon England, although there are two references to Anglo-Saxon pagan priests in the surviving textual sources.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] One is that provided by Bede, which refers to Coifi of Northumbria.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] There have also been suggestions that individuals who were biologically male but who were buried in female costume may have represented a form of magico-religious specialists in Anglo-Saxon England.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] It has been suggested that these individuals were analogous to the *Seiðmenn* recorded in Old Norse sources.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] This possibility is linked to an account provided by Tacitus in his *Germania* in which he refers to a male pagan priest who wore female clothing.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Campbell suggested that it might have been priestly authorities who organised the imposition of physical penalties in early Anglo-Saxon England, with secular authorities only taking on this role during the conversion to Christianity.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Germanic pagan society was structured hierarchically, under a tribal chieftain or *cyning* ("king") who at the same time acted as military leader, high judge and high priest.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The tribe was bound together by a code of customary proper behaviour or *sidu* regulating the contracts (*ǣ*) and conflicts between the individual families or *sibbs* within the tribe.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The aristocratic society arrayed below the king included the ranks of *ealdormann*, *þeġn*, *hēahġerēfa* and *ġerēfa*.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Offices at the court included that of the *þyle* and the *sċop*.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The title of *hlāford* ("lord") denoted the head of any household in origin and expressed the relation to allegiance between a follower and his leader.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Early Anglo-Saxon warfare had many aspects of endemic warfare typical of tribal warrior societies.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] It was based on retainers bound by oath to fight for their lords who in turn were obliged to show generosity to their followers.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The traditional idea was that the pagan Anglo-Saxons inherited the common Germanic institution of sacral kingship.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] A king (*cyning*) was elected from among eligible members of a royal family or *cynn* by the *witena ġemōt*, an assembly of an elite that replaced the earlier folkmoot, which was the equivalent of the Germanic thing, the assembly of all free men.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The person elected was usually the son of the last king.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Tribal kingship came to an end in the 9th century with the hegemony of Wessex culminating in a unified kingdom of England by the 10th century.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The cult of kingship was central to pagan Anglo-Saxon society.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The king was equivalent to the position of high priest.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] By his divine descent he represented or indeed was the "luck" of the people.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The central importance of the institution of kingship is illustrated by the twenty-six synonyms for "king" employed by the *Beowulf* poet.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The title of *Bretwalda* appears to have conveyed the status of some sort of formal or ceremonial overlordship over Britain, but it is uncertain whether it predates the 9th century, and if it does, what, if any, prerogatives it carried.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Patrick Wormald interprets it as "less an objectively realised office than a subjectively perceived status" and emphasises the partiality of its usage in favour of Southumbrian kings.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Cemeteries are the most widely excavated aspect of Anglo-Saxon archaeology and thus much information about the funerary aspects of Anglo-Saxon pagan religion has been obtained.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] One of the aspects of Anglo-Saxon paganism which is the most known most about is their burial customs, discovered from archaeological excavations at various sites, including Sutton Hoo, Spong Hill, Prittlewell, Snape and Walkington Wold, with 1200 Anglo-Saxon pagan cemeteries having been found.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The pagan Anglo-Saxons had no set form of burial, with cremation being preferred among the Angles in the north and burial among the Saxons in the south, although both forms were found throughout England, sometimes in the same cemeteries.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] When cremation did take place, the ashes were usually placed within an urn and then buried, sometimes along with grave goods.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] There are also a number of recorded cases of parts of non-human animals being buried within such graves.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Most common among these was body parts belonging to either goats or sheep, although parts of oxen were also relatively common, and there are also isolated cases of goose, crab apples, duck eggs and hazelnuts being buried in graves.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] It is widely thought therefore that such items constituted a food source for the deceased.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] In some cases, animal skulls, particularly oxen but also pig, were buried in human graves, a practice that was also found in earlier Roman Britain.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Certain Anglo-Saxon burials appeared to have ritualistic elements to them, implying that a religious rite was performed over them during the funeral.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] While there are many multiple burials, where more than one corpse was found in a single grave, that date from the Anglo-Saxon period, there is "a small group of such burials where an interpretation involving ritual practices may be possible".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] For instance, at Welbeck Hill in Lincolnshire, the corpse of a decapitated woman was placed in reverse on top of the body of an old man, while in a number of other similar examples, female bodies were again placed above those of men.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] This has led some archaeologists to suspect a form of suttee, where the female was the spouse of the male, and was killed to accompany him upon death.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Other theories hold that the females were slaves who were viewed as the property of the men, and who were again killed to accompany their master.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Similarly, four Anglo-Saxon burials have been excavated where it appears that the individual was buried while still alive, which could imply that this was a part of either a religious rite or as a form of punishment.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] There are also many cases where corpses have been found decapitated, for instance, at a mass grave in Thetford, Norfolk, fifty beheaded individuals were discovered, their heads possibly having been taken as trophies of war.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] In other cases of decapitation it seems possible that it was evidence of religious ritual (presumably human sacrifice) or execution.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] In some cases, there is evidence of far smaller structures being built around or alongside individual graves, implying possible small shrines to the dead individual or individuals buried there.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Eventually, in the sixth and seventh centuries, the idea of burial mounds began to appear in Anglo-Saxon England, and in certain cases earlier burial mounds from the Neolithic, Bronze Age, Iron Age and Romano-British periods were simply reused by the Anglo-Saxons.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] It is not known why they adopted this practice, but it may be from the practices of the native Britons.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Burial mounds remained objects of veneration in early Anglo-Saxon Christianity, and numerous churches were built next to tumuli.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Another form of burial was that of ship burials, which were practised by many of the Germanic peoples across northern Europe.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] In many cases it seems that the corpse was placed in a ship that was either sent out to sea or left on land, but in both cases burned.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] In Suffolk however, ships were not burned, but buried, as is the case at Sutton Hoo, which it is believed, was the resting place of the king of the East Angles, Raedwald.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Both ship and tumulus burials were described in the *Beowulf* poem, through the funerals of Scyld Scefing and Beowulf respectively.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] It has been considered largely impossible to distinguish a pagan grave from a Christian one in the Anglo-Saxon context after the latter had spread throughout England.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Everything so far known about the religious festivals of the pagan Anglo-Saxons comes from a book written by Bede, titled *De temporum ratione* ("The Reckoning of Time"), in which he described the calendar of the year.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] However, its purpose was not to describe the pagan sacred year, and little information within it can be corroborated from other sources.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Bede provided explanations for the names of the various pre-Christian festivals that he described, however these etymologies are questionable; it is unknown if these etymologies were based on his pre-existing knowledge or whether they represented his own theories.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Casting further doubt over some of his festival etymologies is the fact that some of the place-name etymologies that Bede provides in his writings are demonstrably wrong.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The pagan Anglo-Saxons followed a calendar with twelve lunar months, with the occasional year having thirteen months so that the lunar and solar alignment could be corrected.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Bede claimed that the greatest pagan festival was *Modraniht* (meaning *Mothers' Night*), which was situated at the Winter solstice, which marked the start of the Anglo-Saxon year.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Following this festival, in the month of *Solmonað* (February), Bede claims that the pagans offered cakes to their deities.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Then, in *Eostur-monath Aprilis* (April), a spring festival was celebrated, dedicated to the goddess Eostre, and the later Christian festival of Easter took its name from this month and its goddess.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The month of September was known as *Halegmonath*, meaning *Holy Month*, which may indicate that it had special religious significance.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The month of November was known as *Blōtmōnaþ*, meaning *Blót Month*, and was commemorated with animal sacrifice, both in offering to the gods, and probably also to gather a source of food to be stored over the winter.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Stenton thought that Bede's account reveals "that there was a strong element of heathen festivity" at the heart of the early Anglo-Saxon calendar.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The historian James Campbell described this as a "complicated calendar", and stated that it would have required "an organised and recognised priesthood" to plan the observation of it.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Various recurring symbols appear on certain pagan Anglo-Saxon artefacts, in particular on grave goods.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Most notable among these was the swastika, which was widely inscribed on crematory urns and also on various brooches and other forms of jewellery as well as on certain pieces of ceremonial weaponry.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The archaeologist David Wilson remarked that this "undoubtedly had special importance for the Anglo-Saxons, either magical or religious, or both.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] It seems very likely that it was the symbol of the thunder god Thunor, and when found on weapons or military gear its purpose would be to provide protection and success in battle".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] He also noted however that its widespread usage might have led to it becoming "a purely decorative device with no real symbolic importance".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Another symbol that has appeared on several pagan artefacts from this period, including a number of swords, was the rune ᛏ, which represented the letter T and may be associated with the god Tiw.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] In the later sixth and seventh centuries, a trend emerged in Anglo-Saxon England entailing the symbolism of a horn-helmeted man.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The archaeologist Tim Pestell stated that these represented "one of the clearest examples of objects with primarily cultic or religious connotations".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] This iconography is not unique to England and can be found in Scandinavia and continental Germanic Europe too.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The inclusion of this image on helmets and pendants suggests that it may have had apotropaic or amuletic associations.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] This figure has often been interpreted as a depiction of Woden, although there is no firm evidence to support this conclusion.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] In 2011, Pluskowski noted that the term "shamanism" was increasingly being used by scholars of Anglo-Saxon paganism.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Glosecki argued that evidence for shamanic beliefs were visible in later Anglo-Saxon literature.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Williams also argued that paganism had a shamanic component through his analysis of early funerary rites.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Summarising this evidence, Blair noted that it was "hard to doubt that something like shamanism lies ultimately in the background" of early Anglo-Saxon religion.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] He nevertheless highlighted problems with the use of "shamanism" in this context, noting that any such Anglo-Saxon practices would have been different from the shamanism of Siberia.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Conversely, Noël Adams stated that "at present, there is no clear evidence of shamanistic beliefs" in Anglo-Saxon England.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Anglo-Saxon pagans believed in magic and witchcraft.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] There are various Old English terms for "witch", including *hæġtesse* "witch" (whence Modern English *hag*), *wiċċa*, *ġealdriċġe*, *sċīnlǣċe* and *helrūne*.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The belief in witchcraft was suppressed in the 9th to 10th century as is evident e.g. from the *Laws of Ælfred* (c.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] It is possible that the Anglo-Saxons drew no distinction between magic and ritual in the same manner as modern Western society does.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Similarly, the *U* version of the *Paenitentiale Theodori* condemns those "who observe auguries, omens or dreams or any other prophecies after the manner of the pagans".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The pagan Anglo-Saxons also appeared to wear amulets, and there are many cases in which corpses were buried with them.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Not being native to British seas, the cowrie shells had to have been brought to England by traders who had come all the way from the Red Sea in the Middle East.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Animal teeth were also used as amulets by the pagan Anglo-Saxons, and many examples have been found that had formerly belonged to boar, beaver, and in some cases even humans.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Six of the modern English days of the week derive their names from Anglo-Saxon deities .
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] These names have their origins in the Latin system of week-day names, which had been translated into Old English.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Archaeologists Martin Carver, Alex Sanmark, and Sarah Semple, 2010.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] While historical investigation into Germanic paganism and its mythology began in the seventeenth century with Peder Resen's *Edda Islandorum* (1665), this largely focused only upon Norse mythology, much of which was preserved in Old Icelandic sources.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] In the eighteenth century, English Romanticism developed a strong enthusiasm for Iceland and Nordic culture, expressed in original English poems extolling Viking virtues, such as Thomas Warton's "Runic Odes" of 1748.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] With nascent nationalism in early nineteenth-century Europe, by the 1830s both Nordic and German philology had produced "national mythologies" in N.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Grundtvig's *Nordens Mytologi* and Jacob Grimm's *Deutsche Mythologie*, respectively.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] British Romanticism at the same time had at its disposal both a Celtic and a Viking revival, but nothing focusing on the Anglo-Saxons because there was very little evidence of their pagan mythology still surviving.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Indeed, so scant was evidence of paganism in Anglo-Saxon England that some scholars came to assume that the Anglo-Saxons had been Christianised essentially from the moment of their arrival in Britain.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The study of Anglo-Saxon paganism began only in the mid nineteenth century, when John Kemble published *The Saxons in England Volume I* (1849), in which he discussed the usefulness of examining place-names to find out about the religion.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] This was followed by the publication of John Yonge Akerman's *Remains of Pagan Saxondom* (1855).
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Akerman defended his chosen subject in the introduction by pointing out the archaeological evidence of a "Pagan Saxon mode of sepulture" on English soil lasting from the "middle of the fifth to the middle or perhaps the end of the seventh century".
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] From this point onward, more academic research into the Anglo-Saxons' pagan religion appeared.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] This led to further books on the subject, such as those primarily about the Anglo-Saxon gods, such as Brian Branston's *The Lost Gods of England* (1957), and Kathy Herbert's *Looking for the Lost Gods of England* (1994).
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Others emphasised archaeological evidence, such as David Wilson's *Anglo-Saxon Paganism* (1992) and the edited anthology *Signals of Belief in Early England: Anglo-Saxon Paganism Revisited* (2010).
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The deities of pre-Christian Anglo-Saxon religion have been adopted by practitioners of various forms of modern Paganism, specifically those belonging to the new religious movement of Heathenry.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] The Anglo-Saxon gods have also been adopted in forms of the modern Pagan religion of Wicca, particularly the denomination of Seax-Wicca, founded by Raymond Buckland in the 1970s, which combined Anglo-Saxon deity names with the Wiccan theological structure.
[src:bernicia/anglo-saxon-paganism-p02] Such belief systems often attribute Norse beliefs to pagan Anglo-Saxons.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] The Anglian territory of Bernicia was approximately equivalent to the modern English counties of Northumberland, Tyne and Wear, and Durham, as well as the Scottish counties of Berwickshire and East Lothian, stretching from the Forth to the Tees.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] In the early 7th century, it merged with its southern neighbour, Deira, to form the kingdom of Northumbria, and its borders subsequently expanded considerably.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] The Old English name *Beornice* is the tribal name, translated as 'Bernicians'.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] The name of the kingdom, *Beornica rice*, means 'Realm of the Bernicians'.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] Bernicia occurs in Old Welsh poetry as *Bryneich* or *Byrneich* and in the 9th-century *Historia Brittonum*, (§ 61) as *Berneich*, *Birneich*, *Bernech* and *Birnech*.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] Academics agree the name was originally Celtic.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] This name was then adopted by the Anglian settlers who rendered it in Old English as *Bernice* (Northumbrian dialect) or *Beornice* (West Saxon dialect).
[src:bernicia/bernicia] The counter hypothesis suggesting these names represent a Brythonic adaption of an earlier English form is considered less probable.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] Local linguistic evidence suggests continued political activity in the area from the time of the Roman retreat from Britain and before the arrival of the Angles.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] Analysis of a potential derivation has not produced a consensus.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] The most commonly cited etymology gives the meaning as "Land of the Mountain Passes" or "Land of the Gaps" (tentatively proposed by Kenneth H.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] An earlier derivation from the tribal name of the Brigantes has been dismissed as linguistically unsound.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] Koch suggested the conflation of a probable primary form **Bernech* with the native form **Brïγent* for the old *civitas Brigantum* as a result of Anglian expansion in that territory during the 7th century.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] The Brythonic kingdom of the area was formed from what had once been the southern lands of the Votadini, possibly as part of the division of a supposed 'great northern realm' of Coel Hen in c.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] This northern realm is referred to by Welsh scholars as *Yr Hen Ogledd* or, literally, "The Old North".
[src:bernicia/bernicia] The kingdom may have been ruled from the site that later became the English Bamburgh, which certainly features in Welsh sources as *Din Guardi*.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] Near this high-status residence lay the island of Lindisfarne (formerly known, in Welsh, as *Ynys Medcaut*), which became the seat of the Bernician bishops.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] It is unknown when the Angles finally conquered the whole region, but around 604 is likely.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] There are several Old Welsh pedigrees of princely "Men of the North" (*Gwŷr y Gogledd*) that may represent the kings of the British kingdom in the area, which may have been called *Bryneich*.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] John Morris surmised that the line of a certain Morcant Bulc referred to these monarchs, chiefly because he identified this man as the murderer of Urien Rheged who was, at the time, besieging Lindisfarne.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] Some of the Angles of Bernicia (Old English: *Beornice*) may have been employed as mercenaries along Hadrian's Wall during the late Roman period.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] Others are thought to have migrated north (by sea) from Deira in the early 6th century.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] The first Anglian king in the historical record is Ida, who is said to have obtained the throne and the kingdom about 547.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] His sons spent many years fighting a united force from the surrounding Brythonic kingdoms until their alliance collapsed into civil war.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] Ida's grandson, Æthelfrith (Æðelfriþ), united Deira with his own kingdom by force around 604.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] He ruled the two kingdoms (united as Northumbria) until he was defeated and killed by Rædwald of East Anglia (who had given refuge to Edwin, son of Ælle, king of Deira) around 616.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] The early part of Edwin's reign was possibly spent fighting enemies from the Brythonic exiles of the old British kingdom, operating out of Gododdin.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] After this, it is said that on Easter Day 627 Edwin converted to Christianity in return for Elmet (a Cumbric-speaking kingdom that once existed in the modern-day West Riding of Yorkshire, near Leeds), joining the kingdom of Northumbria; which drew him into direct conflict with Wales proper.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] Following the disastrous Battle of Hatfield Chase on 12 October 633, in which Edwin was defeated and killed by Cadwallon ap Cadfan of Gwynedd and Penda of Mercia, Northumbria was divided back into Bernicia and Deira.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] Bernicia was then briefly ruled by Eanfrith, son of Æthelfrith, but after about a year he went to Cadwallon to sue for peace and was killed.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] Eanfrith's brother Oswald then raised an army and finally defeated Cadwallon at the Battle of Heavenfield in 634.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] After this victory, Oswald appears to have been recognised by both Bernicians and Deirans as king of a properly united Northumbria.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] The kings of Bernicia were thereafter supreme in that kingdom, although Deira had its own sub-kings at times during the reigns of Oswiu and his son Ecgfrith.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] After the decisive defeat of Northumbrian forces by the Viking Great Heathen Army, at the Battle of York in 867, the united Kingdom of Northumbria disintegrated.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] The lands north of the Tyne remained a de facto independent kingdom called Bamburgh after the stronghold of its high-reeves.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] The lands between Tyne and Tees were granted to the Community of St.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] Cuthbert, forming an ecclesiastical buffer zone between Jórvík and Bamburgh.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] In 927 Ealdred accepted West Saxon overlordship; however, the lands north of the Tees remained outside of the West Saxon administrative system of shires and hundreds until after the Norman invasion.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] In 973, Scots sovereignty over northern Bernicia, now known as Lothian, was acknowledged by Edgar of England.
[src:bernicia/bernicia] Under Oswald son of Æthelfrith, Bernicia was united with Deira to form Northumbria from 634 onward until the Viking invasion of the 9th Century.
